points_of_interest.name: The Knockout
points_of_interest.description: A quirky hipster bar with old arcade games and on some nights, live bands of varying talent.

points_of_interest.name: Rock Bar
points_of_interest.description: Neighborhood bar with strong, affordable, and creative cocktails. Owned by the same people as the Front Porch, across the street.

points_of_interest.name: The Royal Cuckoo
points_of_interest.description: A new cocktail bar serving outstanding Manhattans and other more unusual concoctions in a setting that feels like an old hunting lodge. A must if you like sipping bourbon and other aperitifs to old-timey music.

points_of_interest.name: VinoRosso
points_of_interest.description: A great little wine bar with emphasis on Italian varieties.

points_of_interest.name: Wild Side West
points_of_interest.description: Although it's a lesbian bar, this neighborhood watering hole welcomes all. Inexpensive beer flows from the taps. In the winter time, a fire burns in the main room, which includes a small pool table. But the most interesting aspect to this bar is the outside garden in the back, best enjoyed on warmer days and nights. The garden is heavily decorated with sculptures and lights. Find a nook to cuddle up with a loved one while sipping a drink.

points_of_interest.name: Bottom of the Hill
points_of_interest.description: Chosen by ''Rolling Stone'' magazine (RS 813) as "the best place to hear live music in San Francisco", the Bottom of the Hill presents some of the finest original artists, seven nights a week. It has a full bar and a kitchen and also features a nice patio area to escape the crowd and have a smoke.

points_of_interest.name: Farley's Coffee and Newsstand
points_of_interest.description: An institution in Potrero Hill since 1989. Roger (the owner) is a conscientious-objector to cafe wi-fi, so don't expect any. But do expect sociable strangers, shelves-full of community sketchbooks, a pile of tattered old board-games, the best newsstand outside of Civic Center, old Hell's Angels guys socializing with Armani clad architects,  delicious coffee drinks, a toy bin for the kids, and dog-friendly folks outside to pet your dog while you're inside.

points_of_interest.name: Blooms Saloon
points_of_interest.description: One of the few remaining true blue-collar watering holes around, this is very much a neighborhood bar and a great place to go to watch baseball and football games. No around-the-shoulder cuffed-sweaters, khaki pants, or tassle-loafer wearin' folks in this joint, but lots of friendly folks, and during Giants or 49ers games, cheers and boos can be heard from a good block away. One of the best views in the city is from out the back porch, which regrettably is now only open during the day. Not a quiet bar, but the back seating area is a good place to meet friends for a 'mellow' beer and chit-chat after dinner or work. All of the sports watching and local gossip takes place up towards the front. Friendly staff; no airheads allowed.

points_of_interest.name: 440 Castro
points_of_interest.description: Heavy gay bar with a rowdy crowd and lots of bears, but for some this is the definitive Castro bar.

points_of_interest.name: The LookOut
points_of_interest.description: Very popular gay bar with great food, a nice balcony, and a much calmer crowd than the 440 Castro.

points_of_interest.name: Bacchus Wine Bar
points_of_interest.description: Small intimate twenty-seat bar that is a good place to go to get a nice glass of wine or a sake cocktail.

points_of_interest.name: Mix
points_of_interest.description: Billing itself as a "neighborhood bar", Mix has strong drinks and a great back patio.

points_of_interest.name: Hi-Lo Club
points_of_interest.description: A new venture by veterans of the Tenderloin bar scene. Nice, craft cocktails, signature house creations, and an impressive beer menu are set in a swanky new/old interior that intentionally has no TV.

points_of_interest.name: Dubliner
points_of_interest.description: Nice Irish pub. Lots of events, like trivia nights, bingo nights, and $3 drinks from 8-10PM on Su, Th and Sa.

points_of_interest.name: Moby Dick
points_of_interest.description: Great bartenders, cheap strong drinks, music videos, and pinball.

points_of_interest.name: Zeki's Bar
points_of_interest.description: A step up from the Nob Hill Tavern.

points_of_interest.name: Miraloma Club
points_of_interest.description: Neighborhood watering hole with a pool table.

points_of_interest.name: Twin Peaks Tavern
points_of_interest.description: Very nice gay bar with a great atmosphere and nice staff. Historically this was the first gay bar in the US to display its patrons to the public, offering large windows looking IN to the bar. Until this addition, most all gay bars were underground bars/clubs that kept the clientele hidden from the general public.

points_of_interest.name: Bimbo's 365 Club
points_of_interest.description: Bimbo's is a glamorous upscale event venue and nightclub that holds up to 700 people. It has three bars, a dance floor and stage. Robin Williams did his act here quite regularly.
points_of_interest.hours: Box office: M-F 10AM-4PM, Club hours: Vary

points_of_interest.name: Philosopher's Club
points_of_interest.description: A friendly neighborhood bar with a pool table, jukebox and a couple of TVs.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe Flore
points_of_interest.description: Go for the good tea or latte and the prime people watching, not necessarily the food.

points_of_interest.name: La Trappe Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A great beer bar and restaurtant hidden in the lower part of North Beach. Out of the way of most tourists because of its low profile. Huge Belgian Beer selection, and other craft brews from around the world. Restaurant offers mussels and frites - classic Belgian combo. Be prepared to splurge if you go, you can easily drink your way to a hefty bill.

points_of_interest.name: R Bar
points_of_interest.description: A rumbly, simple dive-esque bar in the upper Tenderloin neighborhood. Popular with the bar crawl crowds that make their way around the corner from Polk Street.

points_of_interest.name: Biergarten
points_of_interest.description: Do not expect a picturesque Bavarian scene but you will find familiar beer and food.

points_of_interest.name: Boom Boom Room
points_of_interest.description: A super fun bar with live blues, rock and funk bands.

points_of_interest.name: Yoshi's Jazz Club
points_of_interest.description: The newer version of the famous Oakland club, featuring famous jazz performers as well as hip hop and latin music. Yoshi's restaurant serves excellent though unusually expensive Japanese food in an elegant setting.

points_of_interest.name: Benjamin Cooper
points_of_interest.description: Small, nondescript bar inside the Hotel G.  Walk past the check-in desk, go up the flight of stairs and make a left.  Open the door straight in front of you and you're there.  Cozy atmosphere, good selection of drinks, and a good deal on raw oysters, which is the only food they have available.

points_of_interest.name: Harry's Bar
points_of_interest.description: Good neighborhood bar in Pacific Heights with a casual atmosphere. Popular with local professionals.

points_of_interest.name: The 500 Club
points_of_interest.description: Great neighborhood alterna-hipster bar, but in a good way. Formerly an old man dive bar that's been taken over by the thick black rimmed glasses youngster.

points_of_interest.name: E&O Trading Company
points_of_interest.description: Decked out in an upscale but not trying decor, EO Trading has the kind of cocktail list that impresses but doesn't overwhelm. The menu of small plates and appetizers of Asian fusion cuisine, satay platters and a selection of naan bread is the perfect partner for their lychee martinis and Anchor Steam beers. Happy hour is from 3 to 6PM.

points_of_interest.name: Asiento
points_of_interest.description: Relatively new bar with a great selection of beer, wine, and spirits. Awesome tapas. The "Queso Fundido" is wicked and it packs enough calories to keep you dancing until 4AM. Audio and video feeds of live DJs are streamed in to work around current license restrictions. This place is fun when it's packed and when it's empty.

points_of_interest.name: Irish Bank
points_of_interest.description: An old-style Irish pub, walls adorned with antiques, with a great selection of whiskey, imports, and microbrewed beer, and good pub food.  The Bank has plenty of outdoor sitting, ideal for a warm day.

points_of_interest.name: Beauty Bar
points_of_interest.description: One the few real dance clubs in the Mission, Beauty Bar used to be popular with hipsters but is now mainly populated with a more ghetto crowd.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Exchange
points_of_interest.description: A good selection of microbrews and imports on tap in a typical sports bar.
Lines all night outside during the weekend. A twenty-something meat market.

points_of_interest.name: Blondies
points_of_interest.description: Drinks are not cheap (several dollars more than every other bar on the block, but also twice as large), although to be fair the drinks are well made and strong. Truly good martinis, admittedly.

points_of_interest.name: Starlight Room
points_of_interest.description: Not for a visitor that's light in the wallet, but the view and setting from this lounge are undeniably hard to beat.  Opulent is probably the best description.  Dress well if going as the crowd that attends is there to be seen.

points_of_interest.name: The Cat Club
points_of_interest.description: Thursday is 80s night where you're guaranteed to hear at least one Madonna song throughout the night.

points_of_interest.name: Casanova Lounge
points_of_interest.description: An awesome cross between a stylish lounge and hipster joint with the best ambiance of any Mission bar. DJs spin a wide variety of music nightly. Enjoy the 1970s era velvet paintings of topless women, some posing with wild animals, and the black Burt Reynolds.

points_of_interest.name: Tunnel Top
points_of_interest.description: This two-floor, cash-only bar is a neighborhood staple, where you'll find an eclectic mix of locals downing the very excellent mojitos, shots of Fernet-Branca (the unofficial drink of San Francisco), or egging on the bartenders to make up a new drink.

points_of_interest.name: DNA Lounge
points_of_interest.description: The DNA Lounge is a 2-story club which often caters to the geekier "digerati" crowd. One of the founders is Jamie Zawinski, a former Netscape superstar and Internet nabob. Events feature themed electronica dance nights (Industrial, Techno, Trance, etc.) and live bands.

points_of_interest.name: Dalva
points_of_interest.description: It's very dimly lit but cool decor. Excellent jukebox, though after 9PM they tend to turn it up just a touch too loud. Frequently has great DJs playing funk and R&B but varies; clientele leans toward the gentrification crowd. Lots of smoke from the VIP room in the back filters out into the main bar. Excellent happy hour!

points_of_interest.name: The End Up
points_of_interest.description: An SF institution. Essentially doesn't close on the weekend, and thus where people 'end up'. Great old school SF house music. Unexpected outdoor patio/waterfall space to chill.

points_of_interest.name: Delirium
points_of_interest.description: The Albion was truly a vaguely scary dive bar. Delirium was another great neighborhood bar, but it's shockingly turned into a bit of a bridge and tunnel 20-something meatmarket these days. They have a place to dance in the back, with good 1960s rock and soul on Wednesdays.
points_of_interest.hours: M W Th 4PM-2AM, Tu F 2PM-2AM, Sa Su 1PM-2AM

points_of_interest.name: Mezzanine
points_of_interest.description: Where all the shirtless buff gay boys go. Great sound system. If you like cheesy techno and disco diva wailing music, this is the place.

points_of_interest.name: Doc's Clock
points_of_interest.description: A truly great dive bar with a shuffleboard table and Connect Four, if that's your passion.

points_of_interest.name: The Alembic
points_of_interest.description: Styling itself a 'Whiskey Bar', the Alembic is a place to have classic cocktails as well as original creations. The house Manhattan, made with Rye Whiskey, is phenomenal.

points_of_interest.name: The Stud
points_of_interest.description: Fun semi-dingy club. Don't miss Trannyshack, Tuesdays at midnight. Very worth the sleep deprivation at work the next day.

points_of_interest.name: Elixir
points_of_interest.description: One of the oldest bars in San Francisco, since 1858. Rock music, Pub quiz, charity events, great drink specials and a warm vibe.

points_of_interest.name: Aub Zam-Zam
points_of_interest.description: A 1930s vintage cocktail bar with a beautifully restored arabesque art-deco decor. Written up in 'W' and 'Newsweek' magazines for the best martinis in the US back in the 80s. Drinks are moderately expensive but of exceptional quality, even from the well. An intimate and classy setting for a romantic evening with a juke box that leans toward swing and big band music. Named for the Well of Zamzam, one of the holiest places in Islam, a source of blessed beverages.

points_of_interest.name: 83 Proof
points_of_interest.description: This narrow lounge sits precariously between a Walgreens and a Wachovia. Friendly bartenders will concoct any type of drink you desire, which makes it great for a quick, after-work drink or late-night cocktails. 83 Proof is also well-suited to group outings with its cozy atmosphere and chill vibe. Along with the DJ, weekend nights can get pretty loud sometimes.

points_of_interest.name: Gestalt
points_of_interest.description: Beer bar with a large tap list, some sausages, and a bunch of pinball machines.

points_of_interest.name: Danny Coyle's
points_of_interest.description: Irish pub where the Guinness is served with a smile, and if you're lucky, an Irish accent to match.

points_of_interest.name: City Beer Store & Tasting Bar
points_of_interest.description: Your best bet for beer to go.

points_of_interest.name: Kilowatt
points_of_interest.description: Fun yet intimate bar. Great music on the jukebox (if you like speed metal) and a decent place to play pool or darts or just get a drink. Outstanding bartenders.

points_of_interest.name: Club Deluxe
points_of_interest.description: This small, stylish bar has been around for a long time. It's all about Giovanni's Neapolitan Pizza and freshly squeezed cocktails. Deluxe hosts free comedy on Monday nights and jazz every other night, always by local acts. The bartenders are friendly and the crowd is arty and hip.

points_of_interest.name: District
points_of_interest.description: Old furniture store converted to the latest wine-bar in SoMa.

points_of_interest.name: Latin American Club
points_of_interest.description: Decorated in dusty kitsch, the LAC also has large paintings for sale by local artists. They can offer up some of the best, strongest margaritas in town. Just one, that's all it takes.

points_of_interest.name: Gold Cane
points_of_interest.description: A great place for cheap, strong drinks, and friendly bar-tenders. Divey atmosphere, local crowd. Has a pool table and small outdoor patio for smokers of all types.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Utah Saloon
points_of_interest.description: Popular brewery.

points_of_interest.name: The Liberties
points_of_interest.description: Irish Pub. Excellent late weekend brunch no one knows about.

points_of_interest.name: Hobson's Choice
points_of_interest.description: Offering a selection of well over 100 rums, this "Victorian punch house" themed bar is best known for it's original alcoholic punches that you can order by the glass or by the bowl. (watch out, they're stronger than you think!) The corner location and large windows make it a perfect spot to grab a drink and people-watch. Go on Sundays when they offer a lavish make-your-own Bloody Mary bar with plenty of fixin's. (don't worry, they'll mix it for you if you're not so inclined) A friendly staff and great jukebox brings the locals in early, more of a younger crowd late night and on weekends.

points_of_interest.name: Press Club
points_of_interest.description: This bar focuses on wine, with some of the finest from the nearby Wine Country. Sneak a peek at the wine cellar, and don't be surprised if you're super critical of the next glass of wine you drain outside the Press Club. Be prepared, however, to put a dent in your credit card or wallet by the end of the night.

points_of_interest.name: Monk's Kettle
points_of_interest.description: A small tavern with good pub food that specializes in craft beer.

points_of_interest.name: Kezar Pub & Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: A popular English-themed pub where you can watch soccer.

points_of_interest.name: Phone Booth
points_of_interest.description: Another competitor for the ''definitive dive bar''. Appropriately named given its size. Allows smoking. Free popcorn.

points_of_interest.name: Mad Dog in the Fog
points_of_interest.description: This is an English pub where you can come to watch soccer on TV or go out back where you can smoke. Occasionally live music at night. The hotline for when matches are being played is +1-415-442-7994. Since they open for live matches from England as early as 6AM, its the best place to get a beer before noon in the area on the weekend.

points_of_interest.name: Shotwell's
points_of_interest.description: The definition of a neighborhood bar. Still smoky despite the smoking ban.

points_of_interest.name: Magnolia
points_of_interest.description: Serves solid food and microbrews, including some excellent cask conditioned beers.

points_of_interest.name: Skylark
points_of_interest.description: A bit of a meatmarket 'club' scene. Mostly hip-hop style and "gangster" wannabe crowd, mostly not from the city. Lots of dancing. Clientele is usually very friendly and outgoing and the bartenders handle the busy crowds with aplomb.

points_of_interest.name: Molotov's
points_of_interest.description: Leans towards rockabilly and mohawk crowd. Dog and food friendly.

points_of_interest.name: Uptown
points_of_interest.description: Small neighborhood bar with artsy aging punk rockers and a relaxed attitude. Dogs and bicycles welcome.

points_of_interest.name: Nickie's
points_of_interest.description: Dance club and bar - Grateful Dead night every Monday, and popular dub and funk nights during the week as well.

points_of_interest.name: Zeitgeist
points_of_interest.description: Cool motorcycle/bike courier punk rock-ish alterna-crowd. The bartenders can (and almost always do) often drip with attitude. They, and the regulars, can be fiercely protective of their little hideaway. Awesome and huge backyard (i.e. beer garden). Rowdy on weekend nights and they bbq too.

points_of_interest.name: Noc Noc
points_of_interest.description: A very artsy atmosphere. You can get many Trappist monk beers here. Live DJ nightly. Tarot readings Mondays 6-9PM. Beer, wine and sake (no hard liquor). Alas for smokers: Big Brother finally put down the rebellion and smoking is now relegated to the sidewalk in front.

points_of_interest.name: Pilsner Inn
points_of_interest.description: A low-key, unpretentious gay bar with plenty of room inside.

points_of_interest.name: Toronado
points_of_interest.description: This bar has forty-six beers on tap and a bottled beer menu which covers two whole pages. They serve many microbrews and imports from Germany, Belgium, and Japan. Come through the Dutch door and if there is no room in the front bar, there is a back room with tables. No food is served, but you may bring food in from any of the many restaurants nearby. This is a cash only establishment.

points_of_interest.name: Blur
points_of_interest.description: Upscale, lush, candlelit bar in the Polk Gulch. It's dark and romantic and they have a good selection of cocktails... try the strawberry margarita. They also have free pizza on Monday nights.

points_of_interest.name: Trax
points_of_interest.description: A gay bar for gay men and lesbians that is also very much straight-friendly. Small, divey, and a local's scene. Drinks are cheap, and on Saturday nights it offers ridiculously cheap drink specials ($1 well cocktails before 10PM).

points_of_interest.name: Bourbon and Branch
points_of_interest.description: This hard to find cocktail/spirit themed bar is a throwback to the prohibition days of the 1920s — this address used to be a thriving illegal "speakeasy" known as the "JJ Russell's Cigar Shop." Inside it's ornately decorated with dark woods giving the place a real cozy feel. It being a prohibition themed bar, they also have some strange house rules posted on the walls like ''"no photography"'' and ''"Please speak easy"'' They have an exhaustive selection of spirits and cocktails.

points_of_interest.name: Underground SF
points_of_interest.description: Dance club and bar, formerly called The Top, which features different theme nights, some of which are geared towards alternative culture.

points_of_interest.name: Edinburgh Castle
points_of_interest.description: Expatriates from the British Isles are often to be found at this Scottish pub, which on Thursdays through Saturdays becomes a hipster mecca. The interior is warm and shadowy, a comfortable place of dark wood and golden lantern light, and the beer selection is good; you can get pints of Belhaven or Newcastle as well as the ubiquitous Guinness, and it's all available by the pitcher. The Edinburgh Castle also has a relationship with a local fish and chips fryer, so you can order from their menu and have it delivered to you at the pub. The jukebox is well stocked with punk rock, Irish folk/rock, and American roots music, and live bands also play regularly (which can unfortunately make it impossible to carry on a conversation). A trivia contest is held on Tuesday nights. And on Burns Night (January 25th), the Edinburgh Castle is ''the'' place to be, with ribald poetry readings, music, and a public haggis.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe International
points_of_interest.description: Offers net access, live music, food, and a variety of beverages from coffee, tea, beer, wine to fresh squeezed juices. Good desserts.

points_of_interest.name: Hanaro
points_of_interest.description: Just across from the Edinburgh Castle is a shadowy hole-in-the-wall festooned with Korean lettering: Hanaro. Though the bar is wallpapered with "No Smoking" signs (as California law demands), you need only loiter outside the bar for a few minutes with a cigarette before you are beckoned inside and offered an ashtray. In fact, Hanaro's great charm is it that it's accommodating in every respect; stay for a bit and you will be offered various bar snacks, and there is usually a hostess on hand whose only job is to chat with the patrons. This is done, however, with taste and tact; if you wish to drink in silence, you won't be disturbed. The jukebox is stocked with Asian pop singles.

points_of_interest.name: Coffee to the People
points_of_interest.description: A favorite community gathering spot, Coffee to the People serves giant sandwiches, hearty soups, and organic and fair trade coffee and tea. Their croissant breakfast sandwiches are especially popular with locals. The shop is laptop/work friendly, with free wi-fi and almost a dedicated section to people working around notepads and notebooks. The shop has an overtly political theme and decor and is a good spot for people watching.

points_of_interest.name: Ha-Ra Club
points_of_interest.description: Standard but friendly dive-bar in the Tenderloin that serves cheap drinks. It was co-founded by pro-wrestler Hank Hanastead and boxer Ralph Figari. Great place if you're into the 'Loin's no nonsense dive bars.

points_of_interest.name: The Owl Tree
points_of_interest.description: A small, quiet upscale bar that's great for conversation and relaxation after a long day of wandering around San Francisco. What used to be a dive bar with walls adorned with tacky owl memorabilia, is now another upscale watering hole in the 'Loin, where cocktails have replaced draft beers as the drink of preference. There's still a mosaic owl on the outside though.

points_of_interest.name: Tradition
points_of_interest.description: A dive bar (originally the 441) which was bought and renovated by the same people who own Bourbon & Branch. Featuring house made alcohols and unique mixes, while not cheap, it's a unique experience in a classy wood paneled environment.

points_of_interest.name: Union Square Sports Bar
points_of_interest.description: Crowded and loud, but you can catch just about any game here. This place thinks flatscreen TVs are a type of wallpaper. Food offerings are limited to hot dogs and potato chips.

points_of_interest.name: Aunt Charlie's Lounge
points_of_interest.description: If you haven't already guessed from the name, "Aunt Charlie's" is a transvestite dive bar. It hosts a wide variety of entertainment shows and drag shows that are popular with gays, lesbians, transsexuals, and indeed straight patrons. Cheap, stiff drinks accompanied by endearing, harmless, and vocal co-drinkers, provides for fantastic people-watching.
points_of_interest.hours: M-F noon-2AM, Sa 10AM-2AM, Su and Holidays 10AM-midnight

points_of_interest.name: Mitchell Brothers O'Farrell Theater
points_of_interest.description: Tourists have flocked here for live, nude girls and dirty movies since 1971, when porn star Marilyn Chambers followed her performance in a Mitchell Brothers' film by becoming an Ivory Snow model. The venue is large, clean, and the biggest rip-off in adult entertainment this side of Paris. If possible, avoid this over-priced, over-hyped tourist trap for the Crazy Horse on Market (next to the Warfield) or any of the clubs on Broadway in [[San Francisco/Chinatown-North Beach|North Beach]].

points_of_interest.name: Farm:Table
points_of_interest.description: Very tiny spot with one large "farm table" (thus the name) and limited outdoor seating/standing bars. They serve coffee from nearby Santa Cruz roaster, Verve and have their own delicious sweets and other foods that they make daily. Very popular with the locals.

points_of_interest.name: Hooker's Sweet Treats
points_of_interest.description: Great spot to pick up handmade chocolate caramels, bread pudding, and coffee from local roaster, Sightglass. Very cute interior decorated in an antique style and owned by a Louisiana native.

points_of_interest.name: Soluna Cafe and Lounge
points_of_interest.description: Just a stones throw from the performing arts buildings, it's a great place to grab a cappuccino just before the overture.

points_of_interest.name: Buena Vista Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Famous for its Irish Coffee, supposedly the first to serve it in America, and great views over the bay.

points_of_interest.name: Las Margaritas
points_of_interest.description: A Fruit Margarita in the Cannery anyone?
points_of_interest.address: Del Monte Square, 2nd Level, South Bldg

points_of_interest.name: Lou's Fish Shack
points_of_interest.description: Lou's has live Blues music 7 days a week.

points_of_interest.name: Pier 23 Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Lively and colorful, you can't miss this place on your way down the piers of the Embarcadero. It's part bar, part restaurant, and part cafe — ever popular with locals, it has an outdoor drinking deck.

points_of_interest.name: Ghirardelli Choclaterie and Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Serving premium espresso drinks, pastries, and desserts.

points_of_interest.name: 540 Club
points_of_interest.description: Friendly bar with cool art, above-average beer selection, free wi-fi, and a great Sunday trivia night.

points_of_interest.name: The Bitter End
points_of_interest.description: Two-level Irish bar with billiards, darts, pub food, and Tuesday night trivia.

points_of_interest.name: Li Po's
points_of_interest.description: This dive bar is great to pop into while in Chinatown. Although it has nothing on tap, bottled beer is available. Check out the seedy booths in the back lit by a single red bulb. Or catch a live act in the dimly-lit basement on the weekends.

points_of_interest.name: Durty Nelly's
points_of_interest.description: One of the last authentic Irish pubs in the city, from the fantastic bar food to the Irish laborers that drink there every night.

points_of_interest.name: Bow Bow Cocktail Lounge
points_of_interest.description: 寶寶 Little hole in the wall dive bar, run by the irrepressible hostess/owner Candy Mama, a 50-something woman originally from Taiwan. She's a spitfire and a complete rock star. She'll end up doing shots with you, sneaking shots into your drinks, force-feeding you endless peanuts and making adorable and incessant conversation. The crowd's an eclectic mix, which makes for great people-watching, especially when the karaoke is broken out.

points_of_interest.name: The Little Shamrock
points_of_interest.description: The oldest Irish pub in San Francisco. Here you will find free popcorn for patrons, a few TVs tuned into all manner of sports, eclectic but cozy furniture, a shelf full of games at the back, and a fireplace. With very kind bartenders (and regulars), the Little Shamrock feels like a safe cozy den on any weeknight.

points_of_interest.name: Buddha Lounge
points_of_interest.description: Another favorite dive bar in Chinatown, this is a cramped yet lively place that's great for people watching.

points_of_interest.name: Park Chalet
points_of_interest.description: A pleasant bar with outdoor seating next to Golden Gate park and offering delicious appetizers. Adjacent to the Beach Chalet restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Red's Place
points_of_interest.description: It is the oldest operating bar in Chinatown. It's a quiet place, ideal for conversations.

points_of_interest.name: The Plough & Stars
points_of_interest.description: One of the best Irish bars in San Francisco. Traditional live music almost every night.

points_of_interest.name: 15 Romolo
points_of_interest.description: The hidden bar has a lovely dark red decor. Formerly the "Basque Hotel" this historic hotel and bar becomes quite crowded on one of the busiest blocks during a Friday and Saturday night in North Beach. It's also positioned on a steep street, with a side entrance that seems furtive and secret.

points_of_interest.name: Tommy's Mexican Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Self-proclaimed "Premier Tequila Bar on Earth". A must-visit for tequila and margarita enthusiasts. Arrive early to avoid the (drunken) crowd.

points_of_interest.name: NorthStar Cafe
points_of_interest.description: The North Star is a standard bar that you will find almost everywhere in the U.S. It has pool tables, a bar, and as the evening goes on becomes standing room only. This is a good bar for hanging out with friends and making new ones.

points_of_interest.name: Trad'r Sam
points_of_interest.description: Popular tiki bar featuring specialty blender drinks. Gets loud and crowded on weekends.

points_of_interest.name: Specs
points_of_interest.description: Mariner's hangout and general dive bar in North Beach, this is a hidden gem.

points_of_interest.name: Yancy's Saloon
points_of_interest.description: Lots of seating (wooden tables & chairs), with darts at the back, and also several large screen TVs. They have a nice happy hour (which many grad students from UCSF take advantage of).

points_of_interest.name: Tosca
points_of_interest.description: Another landmark North Beach Cafe/Bar, Tosca is dark but atmospheric interior complete with some cool red-leather booths. The bar is named after the opera Tosca and has an intense list of operas on the jukebox. Willie Brown, former mayor, hangout. It's known for its specialty "Coffeeless Cappuccino" — steamed milk with brandy and chocolate. There are about 15 cappuccinos lined up on the bar ready to serve since they are so popular.

points_of_interest.name: Blue Danube
points_of_interest.description: Small coffee shop with good sandwiches and a few sidewalk tables. Computers and paid wi-fi available. Cash only.

points_of_interest.name: Vesuvio's
points_of_interest.description: This quirky and historic bar was founded in 1948, and is famous for its association with jazz, poetry, and the Beat Generation. Neal Cassidy first made a pit stop here in the mid-1950s, and ever since it became a favorite hangout for literati celebrities, including Jack Kerouac. While you're there, why not order "The Jack Kerouac" — a healthy dose of tequila, rum, and cranberry juice. The bar is located next-door to the iconic City Lights Book store and what is now known as "Jack Kerouac Alley".

points_of_interest.name: Henry's House of Coffee
points_of_interest.description: A good local coffee shop.

points_of_interest.name: The Saloon
points_of_interest.description: Old Blues/Jazz bar that has survived the raucous Barbary Coast and the 1906 earthquake. This is the oldest bar in San Francisco and it certainly looks like it too — it's grotty and rough looking inside and out, and it's extremely loud, but it can also be great fun and a must if you love the Blues.

points_of_interest.name: Java Beach Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Offers coffee, beer and wine, pastries, sandwiches, and the like. Outdoor seating, as well as tables, chairs and couches inside. You will find both locals and tourists filling the chairs on any given night.

points_of_interest.name: Savoy-Tivoli
points_of_interest.description: Roomy, fun open-air bar on Grant Avenue, this bar is a favorite with tourists and locals. It has been around since 1906 and attracts an eclectic yet discerning crowd.

points_of_interest.name: Royal Ground Coffee
points_of_interest.description: Local chain serving good coffee and sandwiches.

points_of_interest.name: Columbus Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Great bar in a huddle of bars around the intersection of Grant Avenue and Green Street. It draws a lively and predominantly young crowd. It does a two-for-one happy hour on beers and also $3 Fernets. Watch out though, it can get crowded.

points_of_interest.name: Simple Pleasures
points_of_interest.description: Small, crowded cafe with very rich coffee and decent snacks, but the reason to go here are the plethora of San Francisco locals who come to hang out and chat. It's a great place to strike up a conversation with someone who you just met, and on weekend evenings they have free live jazz to boot, call them for dates/times.

points_of_interest.name: Grant and Green Saloon
points_of_interest.description: Named after the intersection it resides on is this popular if slightly dingy bar. They have live bands playing every night.

points_of_interest.name: Andytown Coffee Roasters
points_of_interest.description: Andytown is a hipster coffee shop with great coffee, tea, and Irish pastries and soda bread. Their signature drink is the sand piper, which is espresso, soda water, and whipped cream. There is always a long line, but it's worth the wait.

points_of_interest.name: Gino & Carlo Cocktail Lounge
points_of_interest.description: One of a trilogy of bars that line up on Green Street, it's a classic North Beach neighborhood bar. It's colorful, has a great juke box, and attracts lots of locals looking to socialize.

points_of_interest.name: Pixlcat
points_of_interest.description: Good artisan coffee and boba.

points_of_interest.name: Kells Irish Restaurant & Bar
points_of_interest.description: On a secluded narrow street, this is more of an upscale Irish bar and attracts twenty and young thirty-something workers from the nearby Financial District who are looking to unwind. It has another bar upstairs which tends to be quieter.

points_of_interest.name: International Sports Club
points_of_interest.description: Nice little bar with a well worn-in interior, moderately loud jukebox and friendly bar staff. They have cheap prices, a pool table and a couple seats by the door for the smokers. Nice mix of locals and tourists, very low key and down to earth. A very good place to make new friends and gets a good young crowd after about nine.

points_of_interest.name: Red Jack Saloon
points_of_interest.description: Dive Bar, set back a few blocks from the Wharf, it's popular with Eastcoasters and Red Sox fans. Cheap drinks and a decent juke box.

points_of_interest.name: Fuse
points_of_interest.description: Catering to a musical taste that leans towards electronica, Fuse regularly features DJs that spin a variety of house and down tempo. This being San Francisco, the crowd tends to show up on the late side, but when they turn out they arrive in force. Fuse isn't that big, so if you arrive after everyone, be prepared to wait in line. The dance floor is minimal, establishing a space that's more for drinking and enjoying the music than getting funky. However, the quality of music is fun, and the bar staff is very friendly.

points_of_interest.name: Zebra Lounge
points_of_interest.description: Upscale and trendy new lounge and nightclub with DJs and a reasonably sized dance floor. It gets a young crowd.

points_of_interest.name: Vixen Cabaret
points_of_interest.description: Upscale topless club is part fine dining, part dance club.

points_of_interest.name: Caffe Trieste
points_of_interest.description: Has become a North Beach landmark. Although a little bit scruffy, it has excellent coffee — certainly one of the best cups of coffee in North Beach, and it's very popular with the locals. One famous local patron was Jack Kerouac and reportedly Francis Ford Copolla wrote part of the ''Godfather'' here.

points_of_interest.name: Stella Pastry & Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Small elegant cafe/bakery that serves fresh affordable coffee with delicious treats like cannoli and tiramisù available on the side.

points_of_interest.name: Caffe Greco
points_of_interest.description: Probably North Beach's most popular cafe, especially with locals. It has a real European atmosphere and imports its coffee from Italy. Curbside tables add to the ambiance.

points_of_interest.name: Caffe Roma
points_of_interest.description: Excellent coffee but a little bit pricey by comparison.

points_of_interest.name: Bohemian Cigar Store
points_of_interest.description: Excellent espresso and a relaxed, friendly atmosphere with curbside tables that overlook Washington Square. Its cappuccino is prize-winning.

points_of_interest.name: Melt
points_of_interest.description: Excellent bohemian corner cafe/eatery that is right on the edge of Washington Square. It has a relaxed coffee-house atmosphere and is a great place to refuel with a panini, a salad or one of their excellent cheese platters. Often features live entertainment and old movies on a big screen.

points_of_interest.name: XoX Truffles
points_of_interest.description: Run by local Chef Jean-Marc Gorce, this teeny-tiny place is more of an award-winning truffle vendor than coffee shop. However, the coffee is fresh and even if you just order a small house-blend for just $1 you'll get a free truffle (worth 75 cents).

points_of_interest.name: Black Horse London Pub
points_of_interest.description: They advertise this place as the smallest bar in San Francisco... ''"Small Pub, Big Heart."'' It is exactly 7 wide and 19 foot long... not for the claustrophobic! It may be small but this is a fun little bar with a list of "Tenets" on the wall; including ''"Thou Shall give priority seating to all Women in the Bar. (If you need further explication, please see "Exit.")"'' and ''"Thou Shall have one pub and one pub only. (Ours...)."''

points_of_interest.name: Blue Light
points_of_interest.description: Their "Taco Tuesday" is a long standing favorite among locals and features $3 margaritas for the ladies. Guys are equally well served with $2 Coronas, and with $1.50 tacos, who could go hungry?
points_of_interest.hours: Bar: M-F 4PM-2AM, Sa-Su 11AM-2AM Kitchen: Kitchen M-F 5PM-10PM, Sa noon-10PM, Sunday 11AM-10PM

points_of_interest.name: Bus Stop
points_of_interest.description: The Bus Stop has a comfortable "homey" atmosphere with 17 TVs and sports memorabilia on the walls. It attracts a twenty-something/thirty-something crowd.

points_of_interest.name: Mauna Loa Club
points_of_interest.description: Pretty cool little Hawaiian bar decked out in island regalia. They have a nice circular bar, open windows that peer out over Fillmore St, and lots of games inside to keep you occupied. They have a pretty decent happy hour M-F 4PM-7PM, to get your night started.

points_of_interest.name: Monaghan's
points_of_interest.description: Another Irish bar turned sports bar in the Marina district which draws an eclectic crowd. They have a long happy hour that runs M-F 4PM-7PM; and nightly specials including "Ladies Night" on Thursdays where cocktails are half price.

points_of_interest.name: California Wine Merchant
points_of_interest.description: Formerly just a wine retail shop, the California Wine Merchant is now a hip little spot where you can enjoy a few glasses of wine, watch people walk by on Chestnut St, or pick up a few bottles to bring home.

points_of_interest.name: Ottimista Enoteca Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Nice little upscale Italian wine bar that has mostly Italian and Californian wines in their exposed cellar. They have a decent selection of circa 40 wines by the glass; 250 by the bottle. They also serve small plates of food to compliment your wine.

points_of_interest.name: The Comet Club
points_of_interest.description: Good place to go if you like to boogie-on-down to the sounds of the 70s and 80s! It's a bit of a cramped space though and can get crowded as a result.

points_of_interest.name: The HiFi Lounge
points_of_interest.description: The HiFi Lounge is where people come to dance the night away. It also features live DJs, games, and big screen TVs. Happy hour begins at 5PM and they offer $2 Budweisers and $3 well Drinks. Their "Girls of Taste" (wine tasting for women) is not to be missed and is held once a month.

points_of_interest.name: Judy's Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Quaint European style Marina cafe serving healthy portions of food.

points_of_interest.name: La Boulangerie de San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: Traditional French bakery and cafe. The owner was born in Bordeaux France and has a lifetime of baking experience. The cafe sells bread made of organic flour from their very own wheat mill.

points_of_interest.name: Tully's Coffee House
points_of_interest.description: Cozy cafe with decent coffee and wi-fi available. They also have a flat screen in store to keep you up to date with the news. The outdoor seating is also a nice touch.

points_of_interest.name: Union Street Coffee Roastery
points_of_interest.description: Decent coffee, an excellent location, plenty of seating, and very friendly staff are what attract patrons here.

points_of_interest.name: Baby Blues BBQ
points_of_interest.description: Slightly overpriced gourmet BBQ with hot waitresses.

points_of_interest.name: Blue Plate
points_of_interest.description: Expensive but wonderful "New American" cuisine with impressive artwork on the walls, and racy photography in the bathrooms. The macaroni and cheese is a must.

points_of_interest.name: Emmy's Spaghetti Shack
points_of_interest.description: A fun, casual restaurant for hipsters. Do not expect fine dining or "authenticity" - just good spaghetti and big meatballs (the Caesar salad is delish, too). Beware the dangerous dive bar next door.

points_of_interest.name: The Front Porch
points_of_interest.description: Well prepared southern food. Fried chicken and fried okra are favorites.

points_of_interest.name: Martha & Bros
points_of_interest.description: Hands down, the strongest coffee on the strip. Martha & Bros. is part of a six-shop San Francisco chain. The smiling, mostly Hispanic female staff, crack-of-dawn hours (it opens at 5:30AM), big pastries and reasonable prices make the place a favorite of newspaper readers, working men and the California Highway Patrol.

points_of_interest.name: Mitchell's Ice Cream
points_of_interest.description: Mitchell's has been serving the best ice cream and sorbets in SF since 1953. Choose from traditional fare or exotic flavors such as avocado, buko (baby coconut), guava, langka (jackfruit), macapuno (sweet coconut), mango, pineapple and ube (purple yam).

points_of_interest.name: 24th Street Cheese Company
points_of_interest.description: Carries hundreds of cheeses where you can taste before you buy.

points_of_interest.name: Moki's Sushi & Pacific Grill
points_of_interest.description: This peach-walled fish chop shop serves fun maki rolls, including a variety with tempura'd ingredients. Its also got killer barbeque spare ribs with wasabi mashed potatoes and steamed greens on its small-plates menu. A good time, often packed, so get there early.

points_of_interest.name: Eric's
points_of_interest.description: California Chinese cuisine (e.g.: many vegs are fresh, white or brown rice, mu shu comes with grilled flour tortillas) with a nod towards Hunan and Mandarin styles. Tasty food in a bustling place. Accessible, vegetarian friendly, beer and wine. Minimum charge of $8 per person.

points_of_interest.name: Moonlight Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A creperie with some great taste sensations. If you're hungry, the Mediterranean platter will fill you up. The toasted bagels with cream cheese, sun-dried tomato and cucumber are perfect, as is the lavender or ginger lemonade.

points_of_interest.name: Firefly
points_of_interest.description: A favorite neighborhood restaurant among locals with creative home cooking and friendly service. Vegan and gluten-free options. Not usually too noisy. Reservations recommended, especially on weekends.

points_of_interest.name: Nute's
points_of_interest.description: A cozy neighborhood favorite serving fresh Thai, ramen, and a selection of Japanese craft beers.

points_of_interest.name: Haystack Pizza
points_of_interest.description: A neighborhood favorite with a full menu with many choices for various diets.

points_of_interest.name: Progressive Grounds
points_of_interest.description: A perfect Bernal Heights cafe. Serves up some great coffee drinks and a good selection of salads and lavash wrapped sandwiches. The hummus will make anyone think twice about buying hummus from a grocery store again. Great service. A great place for all types and ages. Kids have their fun with Enzo and his assorted instruments every Sunday. PG also has a nice garden space in the back.

points_of_interest.name: Old Clam House
points_of_interest.description: Established in 1861. Start your meal with clam broth and sourdough bread.

points_of_interest.name: Hot Cookie
points_of_interest.description: Bakery known for their macaroon cookies distinctively shaped like a piece of male anatomy.

points_of_interest.name: Taqueria Can-cun (not to be confused with Cancun)
points_of_interest.description: Simply the best taqueria in San Francisco, especially if you've had a few drinks at the Knockout or Argus Lounge. The Quesadilla Suiza with some horchata to sip on is just killer.

points_of_interest.name: Roadhouse Coffee Company
points_of_interest.description: Coffee, and a variety of sandwiches.

points_of_interest.name: Kasa Indian Eatery
points_of_interest.description: Indian food in a casual setting emphasizing from-scratch cooking with fresh ingredients.

points_of_interest.name: Zante Pizza
points_of_interest.description: Indian pizza! Need we say more?

points_of_interest.name: Hard Knox Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Casual soul food; oxtail, ribs, fried chicken, etc.

points_of_interest.name: Bullshead Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: A steakhouse well known for their excellent buffalo burgers.

points_of_interest.name: La Ciccia
points_of_interest.description: Gourmet Sardinian food, Italianate but often surprisingly spiced. Large list of unusual Sardinian and other Italian wines.

points_of_interest.name: Big 4 Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: In the Huntington Hotel. Closed until further notice as of February 2023.

points_of_interest.name: 7-Mile House
points_of_interest.description: The 7-Mile House is a historic landmark and a great place to get some food. During the days of the gold rush, the 7-mile house served as a resting post for horse coaches travelling from San Francisco (Embarcadero) to San Jose. This was a place to rest your horses, get some beer and share stories of finding gold. Today, the place boasts an authentic gold rush decor, great beer and burgers and live music most days of the week.

points_of_interest.name: Bi-Rite Grocery
points_of_interest.description: How do they get that much good produce and that incredible deli counter into that storefront? Essential neighborhood and picnic-in-the-park resource. Dolores Park is handily enough a block away, and you're likely to find festivals, rallies, or the SF Mime Troupe at the start and close of their summer touring season there along with kids, dogs and tennis players.

points_of_interest.name: Bursa
points_of_interest.description: A glossy Mediterranean and Turkish restaurant with a large menu.

points_of_interest.name: Lovejoy's Tea Room
points_of_interest.description: Combination antique store and one of the best places to have a cosy high tea in the city. Pub fare also served. Minimum charge $12 per person.

points_of_interest.name: Crustacean Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Mixed reviews about this Vietnamese restaurant, so make your own decision. However, the roast crab has consistently garnered good reviews.

points_of_interest.name: The Grove Fillmore
points_of_interest.description: This cafe style restaurant has got a wholesome Californian menu with staples like salads, bagels, sandwiches, cheese plates, etc.  They also do a very affordable breakfast where you can get options like "Huevos Rancheros" and "Country baked eggs" for under 10 bucks.

points_of_interest.name: Goat Hill Pizza
points_of_interest.description: Great family pizza place.

points_of_interest.name: Valencia Whole Foods
points_of_interest.description: Organic produce and groceries, good bulk foods, and a deli with organic salads, Middle Eastern foods, and sandwiches to order. A neighborhood essential.

points_of_interest.name: Creightons
points_of_interest.description: Local coffee shop and bakery.

points_of_interest.name: Noe Valley Bakery
points_of_interest.description: Considered one of the best local bakeries in the area. They supply some of the better SF restaurants as well as neighborhood demand for baked goods.

points_of_interest.name: Frascati
points_of_interest.description: A pan-European that is somewhat fancy but still relaxed and features local food.

points_of_interest.name: Absinthe
points_of_interest.description: Restyles the rustic foods of southern France into sleek urban classics. Wonderful (expensive) cocktails based on 100-year old recipes. Not the cheapest place in town, but affordable and the quality of the food is an excellent value. A pretty, white-tablecloth setting and excellent service make this a lovely lunch spot. Avoid weekend evenings before 8PM, when crowds from the nearby theater district can mean a wait. And they now serve absinthe.

points_of_interest.name: Plow
points_of_interest.description: popular place for brunch

points_of_interest.name: Bissap Baobab
points_of_interest.description: A Senegalese restaurant with roots in West African Senegalese culture.

points_of_interest.name: Fresca
points_of_interest.description: A small but popular and great Peruvian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Pomelo
points_of_interest.description: Small, quiet restaurant with an affordable variety of international dishes.

points_of_interest.name: Harris' Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Excellent steak house; luxurious dining (plush seats, table cloths, brass chandeliers, etc.).

points_of_interest.name: Fuku-Sushi Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: While Fuku can be pricey, the quality of the sushi is excellent and well worth it. This is one of the best sushi restaurants in a city packed with hundreds. The atmosphere is low key and if you can sit at the bar, Nobu is wonderful to chat with. The service is exceptional and more in line with a traditional Japanese sushi house.

points_of_interest.name: Marcella's Lasagneria
points_of_interest.description: Seven kinds of lasagna, plus salads and other pasta dishes.  Lunch only.  Daily special includes smaller serving with either a small green salad or a cup of soup.  Takeout option is available hot or cold, in case you want to pick up now and heat up later.  Call a day or two in advance if you want to order a whole pan of lasagna for take out (about $80 for 8 people).

points_of_interest.name: Boogaloo's
points_of_interest.description: Hipster-ed up diner, only open for lunch & breakfast. Long lines on the weekends, but surprisingly it moves quickly. Much better vegan breakfast option than Herbivore. Try the plantain cake and the mimosas.

points_of_interest.name: Java on Ocean Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A locally owned coffee shop with sandwiches and Middle Eastern fare. Get a quick bite to eat or stay and have a cappuccino while surfing the internet. They provide paid terminals or paid wireless access through the ZRNet subscription service. The owners have outfitted this joint with Salvation Army sofas and chairs and play eclectic music on the stereo.

points_of_interest.name: Sausage Factory
points_of_interest.description: An Italian restaurant that's larger than it looks from the outside, extending back into the middle of the block. Delivery.

points_of_interest.name: Nara Sushi
points_of_interest.description: Popular with locals that rave about the freshness of the sushi here. Solid sushi at good prices, and large quantities too.

points_of_interest.name: Isobune
points_of_interest.description: As the floating sushi bars so popular in Japan, the sushi chefs at Isobune prepare food and place it on wooden boats that sail around the inner perimeter of an oval counter. Patrons seated at the counter simply lift the dishes they want off the bobbing boats. Your bill depends on the number of empty dishes you're left with. It's fun, cheap, and delicious.

points_of_interest.name: Cha Cha Cha
points_of_interest.description: Excellent tapas in a brick-walled dining room with a bar dominating the center of the room. Expect a loud, party atmosphere, not a quiet, romantic setting. The Cajun Shrimp and the Fried Platanos Maduros are heavenly.

points_of_interest.name: New Tsing Tao Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: A superb Chinese restaurant with large portions and good take-out service.

points_of_interest.name: Savor
points_of_interest.description: A popular brunch spot.

points_of_interest.name: Nob Hill Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A north Italian bistro that serves dinner.

points_of_interest.name: Little Star Pizza
points_of_interest.description: The Chicago deep dish here is among the best in the city.

points_of_interest.name: Foreign Cinema
points_of_interest.description: Dinner and a movie. The Laszlo Bar. A little splurgy and quite fine. Reservations recommended.

points_of_interest.name: Squat & Gobble Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Part of a San Francisco chain, this is a pleasant breakfast place with some excellent crepes. Good place to take the kids.

points_of_interest.name: Thai House
points_of_interest.description: Excellent Thai food in a gay atmosphere, with some dishes that are not on the menu of most American Thai restaurants, such as Kao Soy, chicken with soft and crispy noodles in mustard sauce.

points_of_interest.name: Okoze Sushi
points_of_interest.description: A good sushi restaurant very near the cable car lines on Hyde Street. There is typically no need for a reservation.

points_of_interest.name: On the Bridge
points_of_interest.description: This ultra-cute little eatery, on the bridge connecting the Kintetsu and Kinokuniya Buildings, specializes in an intriguing Euro-Japanese and Indo-Japanese hybrid cuisine called yoshoku, which has been popular in Japan for more than 100 years. Japanese 'pastas' and curried rice plates take on unexpected but delightful flavors.

points_of_interest.name: Jay's Cheesesteak
points_of_interest.description: Niman Ranch beef, or seitan veggie/vegan sandwich options. Great garlic fries!

points_of_interest.name: Taqueria Miraloma
points_of_interest.description: A hidden gem of a taco stand (and truly a "stand", it's take-out only) in the Miraloma neighborhood, with excellent burritos.

points_of_interest.name: Alice's Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Good, not fanciful Chinese food, and quiet enough that you can talk to your dinner companions.

points_of_interest.name: Daffodil Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Serving seasonal, organic cuisine with wines from around the world.

points_of_interest.name: Ristorante Milano
points_of_interest.description: Pleasant Italian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Mifune
points_of_interest.description: Wheelchair Accessible. Looking like a '60s movie-set depiction of a Japanese house, Mifune is one of San Francisco's most popular noodle parlors. A mere $5 will set you up with a hearty bowl of udon or soba noodles, either in a bowl of hot broth or served cold with a dipping cup of sauce. Many delicious vegetarian selections are available.

points_of_interest.name: Little Star Pizza
points_of_interest.description: For a deep dish that can't be beat here, in Chicago, or anywhere else.

points_of_interest.name: Tower Burger
points_of_interest.description: Burgers made from Niman Ranch beef are a specialty here.

points_of_interest.name: John's Grill
points_of_interest.description: Seafood and steak joint.

points_of_interest.name: Za Gourmet Pizza
points_of_interest.description: A good, cheap pizza-by-the-slice restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Sapporo-Ya Japanese Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Excellent Japanese noodles served dozens of ways. Open very late, and a good place to warm up on a cold foggy day.

points_of_interest.name: Cafe du Soleil
points_of_interest.description: Owned by a Moroccan French ex-Pat, this popular cafe serves coffee, pastries, salads, sandwiches, soups, and homemade potato chips. The food can be overpriced, but the atmosphere makes it a popular local hangout. Beer & wine bar, live free jazz most Sundays 5-8PM, and some outdoor seating for a pleasant day. Chic, casual, family friendly. Free Wi-Fi, but limited power outlets.

points_of_interest.name: Philz Coffee
points_of_interest.description: The place for serious coffee drinkers. Choose from a wide variety of beans from all over the world, light, medium or dark roast.

points_of_interest.name: S&E Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Midwestern American food as seen through Hong Kong eyes: complete meals include soup, roll, coffee or HK milk tea, entree, rice or spaghetti, Jello or Chinese bean soup dessert. Extensive list of unusual beverages from Ovaltine to Ginger Coke to green tea milk shakes; Chinese food available after 10PM only. Coffee shop ambiance with TVs at low volume usually tuned to a Chinese station.

points_of_interest.name: Little Delhi
points_of_interest.description: This is a very good Indian restaurant at very reasonable prices. Decor and ambiance is average, but high on taste and cleanliness.

points_of_interest.name: Smitten Ice Cream
points_of_interest.description: Excellent made to order with liquid nitrogen ice cream.

points_of_interest.name: Citrus Club
points_of_interest.description: This is an excellent noodle house with dishes chosen from all Asian traditional cuisines. Portions are generous, with an emphasis on flavor over presentation. Decent prices and an unpretentious decor make for a pleasurable group meal.

points_of_interest.name: Picaro
points_of_interest.description: If you like authentic tapas, the way they were before "small plates" were all the rage, then you'll definitely love the reasonably priced, authentic and generously portioned Spanish dishes here. Don't forget to try their Sangria.

points_of_interest.name: Safeway
points_of_interest.description: A large chain grocery store with a decent selection.

points_of_interest.name: Macy's Cellar Food Court
points_of_interest.description: Around the corner from the swanky appliances on Macy's basement level is basically a food court, but better than the usual with Boudin, a sushi bar, Ben & Jerry's, Tom's Cookies and more. Beware though, it's usually a madhouse.

points_of_interest.name: SPQR
points_of_interest.description: Beautiful European stylized restaurant with a great menu of Italian cuisine and wine, serving walk-ins only - keeping the clientèle local and less stuffy than reservation only dinning.
points_of_interest.hours: M-Tu 11:30AM-2:30PM and 5PM-10PM, W-Th 5PM-10PM, F 5PM-11PM, Sa 11:30AM-11PM, Su 11:30AM-10PM

points_of_interest.name: Estela's Fresh Sandwiches
points_of_interest.description: The name speaks true. Also try Estela's delicious fruit smoothies.

points_of_interest.name: Puerto Alegre
points_of_interest.description: Local favorite, Puerto Alegre churns out inexpensive, delicious Mexican food & margaritas in a fun, festive environment. Divey atmosphere, but that's what you come to the Mission for. Very long wait on the weekends, but absolutely worth it. Host rules the restaurant with an iron fist, so don't try to sneak in!

points_of_interest.name: One Market Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Organic food dishes.

points_of_interest.name: Suppenküche
points_of_interest.description: For casual German food and service, beer -- of course -- served at shared tables.

points_of_interest.name: Kate's Kitchen
points_of_interest.description: Breakfast - Southern style. If you're really hungry, try the French Toast Orgy. Expect a long wait for weekend brunch (just like everywhere else in San Francisco).

points_of_interest.name: Ritual Roasters Coffee
points_of_interest.description: Among the best coffee in the city. Organic beans roasted locally, each cup made fresh individually. A large seating area with free wi-fi.

points_of_interest.name: Pinecrest Diner
points_of_interest.description: Traditional diner fare in a traditional diner setting. If you're looking for a good diner breakfast in the Union Square area, this is the place.

points_of_interest.name: Sacred Grounds
points_of_interest.description: This is the oldest remaining coffeeshop cafe in the Haight-Ashbury. Except for the free Wi-Fi, you almost feel like you are back in the 1960s, with low prices, simple food and a low key neighborhood vibe. Good vegetarian soups and chili. Sandwiches, snacks and desserts. And coffees. Check out the original '60s wallpaper in the bathroom.
points_of_interest.hours: 9AM-5PM daily; 8AM on weekdays; a few evenings too

points_of_interest.name: Love 'n Haight
points_of_interest.description: Often overlooked, but a neighborhood favorite. A family-owned sandwich joint with an Asian flair. Meat and fake meat sandwiches made to order. Try the "veg" duck.

points_of_interest.name: Reds Java House
points_of_interest.description: Have the hamburger, fries and Lagunitas IPA combo.

points_of_interest.name: Serrano's Pizza
points_of_interest.description: Buy a "slice" for under $3 or add toppings for a few cents more, and they'll make a fresh-to-your order triangular slice-shaped pizza that overlaps a dinner plate at three points. Free delivery. Cash or credit, no checks.

points_of_interest.name: Puccini & Pinetti
points_of_interest.description: Popular Italian restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Mel's Drive-In
points_of_interest.description: Mel's Diner This all day, late night diner is a classic bit of Americana, full of shiny stainless steel walls and counters. It's covered in American Graffiti movie posters and outtake photos, since part of the film was shot in this small chain's Lombard St. diner. Good solid comfort food, free parking, with good desserts and ice cream treats. A jukebox control at every table, sucking down your quarters to hear hits from the 1950s.

points_of_interest.name: Metro Caffe
points_of_interest.description: Burgers and cheesesteaks.

points_of_interest.name: 21st Amendment
points_of_interest.description: Good "California-style microbrew" beers. Classic brew pub-grub - burgers, fish, some salads. The Jerk Chicken is excellent. Full menu and images are online. Great place to have drinks before or after a Giants game.

points_of_interest.name: Taqueria Cancun
points_of_interest.description: Commonly touted as having the best vegetarian burrito in SF. If you're a meat-eater, try the Alambres (beef, peppers, onions, and bacon sauteed together, served with beans, rice, tortillas and (optional) avocado.

points_of_interest.name: Schroeder's
points_of_interest.description: A traditional German beer hall with schnitzel, sausages and other delights (and, of course, a good selection of German beers).

points_of_interest.name: Jardiniere
points_of_interest.description: French food in American style, quite pricey, great decor, appetizers, desserts, mixed reviews on entrées. They have both an "à la carte" and a "prix-fixe" menu.
points_of_interest.hours: DSu-W 5PM-10:30PM, Th-Sa 5PM-11:30PM, hours are extended to accommodate neighborhood performances

points_of_interest.name: Rosamunde Sausage Grill
points_of_interest.description: Delicious sausages and not much else. Now with a vegan choice! Get here early Tuesday (11AM) to get in line for their once a week burgers. They sell out instantly! Get it for here, to go, or bring it next door to Toronado and have it with some beer.

points_of_interest.name: Delancey Street Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: It's not just a restaurant, it's a training school for the Delancey Street Foundation - an organization that helps people rebuild their lives from scratch. Nice backdrop of the San Francisco Bay and cheap eats to boot.

points_of_interest.name: Taqueria El Castillito
points_of_interest.description: While everyone has their favorite Mission taqueria, this one may legitimately have a claim to the 'best salsa verde' throne, which is filled with serious avocado chunks. Also, they grill (rather than steam) their tortillas, a key burrito preparation issue.

points_of_interest.name: Tadich Grill
points_of_interest.description: The longest operating restaurant in California, dating back to the Gold Rush. You'll find delicious seafood and a classic atmosphere where groups can sit in their own wood-paneled quarters. Price range is high with most entrees over $20.

points_of_interest.name: Axum Cafe
points_of_interest.description: This Ethiopian restaurant is very affordable. Try the vegetarian sampler. If you are hungry, order for two. Wash it down with an Ethiopian beer (2 kinds).

points_of_interest.name: Hidive
points_of_interest.description: This is where SoMa residents go for quick meetings and meals. You can also find decent food here to go along with the great waterfront views.

points_of_interest.name: Taqueria El Farolito
points_of_interest.description: Gigantic super burritos. Grilled chicken and steak are really great. Super steak quesadilla is the highlight of the menu. Open till 3AM on Friday and Saturday, 1AM the rest of the week. Nachos are enormous. Expect a line of drunks after midnight.

points_of_interest.name: Wexler's
points_of_interest.description: Gourmet BBQ: try the New Orleans-style Flounder Po' Boy, BBQ Brisket Banh Mi, and the Bowl O' Red beanless chili made from smoked short ribs, shallots, and creme fraiche.

points_of_interest.name: Cha-Cha-Cha
points_of_interest.description: Popular Cuban tapas place. Good sangria. Typical wait is 1–2 hours on weekends, and they don't take reservations. Great bar, always crowded with a fun 'artsy' crowd. Be warned, the sangria packs a punch!

points_of_interest.name: Manora's Thai Cuisine
points_of_interest.description: A favorite Thai place among locals, they serve up a great Pad Thai and Thai soups.

points_of_interest.name: Tartine
points_of_interest.description: One of the Bay Area's best bakeries; rich, decadent, and pricey.
points_of_interest.hours: M 8AM-7PM, Tu W 7:30AM-7PM, Th F 7:30AM-8PM, Sa 8AM-8PM, Su 9AM-8PM

points_of_interest.name: Mr. Charlie's
points_of_interest.description: Across the street from a McDonald's is this all-vegan McDonald's parody restaurant, serving "Frowny Meal"s and "not a hamburger"s. The Andy Warhol–inspired wall art, numerous frowny faces, and booths shaped like takeout boxes complete the eccentric theme. The food is reasonably good too, including what is probably the cheapest vegan burger you'll find of comparable quality in the area.

points_of_interest.name: The Grind
points_of_interest.description: Coffee shop with breakfast, lunch, and an amazing array of desserts, pastries, and munchies. Indoor and patio seating.

points_of_interest.name: Rocket Sushi
points_of_interest.description: Delicious sushi served by small robotic rocket trains.

points_of_interest.name: We Be Sushi
points_of_interest.description: The best of a handful of locations of this restaurant, truly "sushi like mom used to make". Try the early bird special.

points_of_interest.name: Indian Oven
points_of_interest.description: This Indian restaurant is on the expensive side, although it is pretty good. Expect a wait any day of the week.

points_of_interest.name: Arizmendi Bakery
points_of_interest.description: This is a great, popular co-op bakery and pizzeria. One kind of pizza per day, which is almost always delicious. The bakery includes traditional items like muffins, scones, and crumb cake (in a home-made style) as well as off-beat items like "chocolate things."

points_of_interest.name: Memphis Minnie's
points_of_interest.description: Great southern-style barbecue and (oddly enough) sake. Amazing mac-n-cheese.

points_of_interest.name: Thirsty Bear Brewing Company
points_of_interest.description: Brewpub meets tapas bar. Good beer brewed in-house, from very light lagers through a nice Kozlov Stout. One or two brews on nitrogen. Very good small-plate food with a Mediterranean/Spanish flair. Tuesday is cask-ale night - beer served from traditional wood cask instead of modern steel - while it lasts, which usually isn't very long.

points_of_interest.name: Art's Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Tiny traditional diner with some Korean specials.

points_of_interest.name: Mythic Pizza
points_of_interest.description: Pizza by the slice.

points_of_interest.name: Yank Sing
points_of_interest.description: This is the place for dim sum, and thus you might need to wait 30 minutes (at most) to have a table. You do not need a menu to order your food; the staff lets you choose what you want to eat from carts pushed around from the dining room. The shrimp, dumplings, and duck here are delicious. The setting of the restaurant is also wonderful.

points_of_interest.name: Naan 'n' Chutney
points_of_interest.description: Indian and Pakistani.

points_of_interest.name: Cheung Hing Chinese Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Cantonese BBQ classics and the best roast duck in the city.

points_of_interest.name: Pork Store Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Extremely popular breakfast spot. Always a line on the weekends. Very inexpensive and friendly diner atmosphere and food.

points_of_interest.name: Gordo's
points_of_interest.description: Cheap, reliable, rapid burritos and tacos.

points_of_interest.name: Thep Phenom
points_of_interest.description: Sometimes called the best Thai in San Francisco; call ahead as this restaurant can be very busy. Or walk in with a small party and have a Singha in the back while you wait to be seated at a family-style table.

points_of_interest.name: Ananda Fuara
points_of_interest.description: This vegetarian restaurant is a little different as it's run by an Indian religious order called 'Sri Chinmoy'. Ananda Fuara means the "Fountain of Delight" and their food is intended to harmonize you both inside and out.

points_of_interest.name: Joe's Ice Cream
points_of_interest.description: A classic American ice cream parlor with an Asian twist.
points_of_interest.hours: Su, Tu-Th 11AM-10PM, F-Sa 11AM-11PM, closed Mondays (grill closes at 9PM)

points_of_interest.name: Minas Brazilian Restaurant & Cachaçaria
points_of_interest.description: Traditional Brazilian food, very affordable, but mixed reviews on service.

points_of_interest.name: Chutney
points_of_interest.description: Affordable and excellent selection of authentic Indian food. Speedy service and filling portions, and free Chai tea for all customers. A recent addition and a neighborhood favorite.

points_of_interest.name: Khan Toke Thai House
points_of_interest.description: An excellent and reasonably priced Thai restaurant with much better ambiance than your average Thai place.

points_of_interest.name: Haight Street Market (aka Gus's)
points_of_interest.description: Family-owned grocery store serving the Upper Haight since 1981. Well-stocked, and with a good range of organic fruit and veg. Also has a deli counter that makes a wide range of sandwiches, which can be eaten at the parklet outside.

points_of_interest.name: Joey's Laundry
points_of_interest.description: What is a laundry doing under 'Eat'? Joey's serves Mitchell's Ice Cream, widely recognized as the best in the Bay Area. If you're bored with chocolate, strawberry, and vanilla, try the green tea or macapuno ice creams. For the launderer seeking more solid sustenance — or if you get hungry while using their internet access ($7.50 per hour) — there are breakfast pastries, pizza slices, and coffee.

points_of_interest.name: King's Thai Cuisine
points_of_interest.description: King of Thai Noodle House Cheap and consistently good.

points_of_interest.name: Moulin Rouge Breakfast Cafe
points_of_interest.description: If you can't stomach the line (or the hipster clientele) at Dottie's, the Moulin Rouge Breakfast Cafe around the corner on Geary offers solid grub at much cheaper prices. The elderly couple who run the place are always friendly and never hurry you, and the shabby faux-French decor is weirdly charming despite liberal amounts of duct tape holding the place together.

points_of_interest.name: The Olympic Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Spacious, affordable and home-cooked breakfast joint. Excellent omelettes. This is a viable alternative of Dottie's True Blue Cafe which almost always seems to have a line.

points_of_interest.name: Pakwan
points_of_interest.description: Pakistani food featuring curries, tandoori fish, and piping hot naan. Unlike some of the local eateries in the "tandoor-loin," the seating is clean, comfortable, and fairly new (possibly the results of some other restaurant's going-out-of-business sale). The restaurant tends to be comparatively quiet, as well as offering an excellent view of police actions on Jones St.

points_of_interest.name: Le Soleil
points_of_interest.description: Gourmet Vietnamese cuisine. Try the soft shell crabs and the appetizer platter - yum!

points_of_interest.name: Shalimar
points_of_interest.description: Northern Indian/Pakistani food, they have a tandoor (clay oven) which means excellent ''naan'' (flat breads) and ''murgh boti'' (barbecue chicken). The curries and rice pilaf are also worth checking out for their unique combination of spices.

points_of_interest.name: Ming Tai Wun-Tun Noodle
points_of_interest.description: Huge shrimp wontons/shui gow/shrimp dumplings.

points_of_interest.name: Tommy's Joynt
points_of_interest.description: Open since 1947, Tommy's is a classic San Francisco eatery and bar. You can't miss this place — on both the inside and out it's colorful and quirkily decorated. They serve wholesome, filling food like "hand-carved" sandwiches, stews, and mash potatoes.

points_of_interest.name: Pho Phu Quoc
points_of_interest.description: PPQ Beef A neighborhood favorite. Savory and affordable Vietnamese dishes in a crowded, bustling atmosphere. Excellent rice and noodle dishes.

points_of_interest.name: Cantoo Latin Asian Rotisserie
points_of_interest.description: A restaurant that features a unique spin to Chinese food, combining Chinese with Venezuelan tastes and dishes. The chili oil pan-fried pork dumplings, the fried calamari or the stir fry beef flat rice noodles are recommended.

points_of_interest.name: Polly Ann Ice Cream
points_of_interest.description: Boasts a collection of over 500 homemade flavors. Fifty-four flavors are available daily.

points_of_interest.name: Bodega Bistro
points_of_interest.description: In Vietnamese ''Bo''-''de''-''ga'' in Vietnamese means ''beef''-''lamb''-''chicken'' — all popular Vietnamese dishes. The menu also draws equal inspiration from French cuisine making this an unusual dining experience.

points_of_interest.name: Bistro Boudin
points_of_interest.description: Home of the sourdough bread with a recipe they've nurtured since 1849, where you can get (among other things) their popular clam chowder in a bread bowl. This is the flagship location of Boudin, where you can shop for gifts here or stroll around their museum to learn about Boudin's history.

points_of_interest.name: Quan Ngon
points_of_interest.description: Northern Vietnamese.

points_of_interest.name: The Douglas Room
points_of_interest.description: Restaurant with well-stocked bar and simple pub fare. Italian Hoagie on the menu strives for authenticity -- the Douglas Room insists on importing Amoroso Rolls from Philadelphia for their hoagie.

points_of_interest.name: Boudin Cafe
points_of_interest.description: A cafe where you can get Boudin food on Pier 39.

points_of_interest.name: Sunrise Deli and Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Awesome falafel.

points_of_interest.name: Kim Thanh
points_of_interest.description: Check out the aquariums in the window if you want to know what's for dinner. If you've never seen a geoduck, you will not soon forget it.

points_of_interest.name: Chowder and crab sidewalk stands
points_of_interest.description: Get clam chowder in a bread bowl, Dungeness crab (in season November through June), fish and chips, shrimp cocktails, calamari salad, etc. from this busy outdoor marketplace. If you're getting a crab, ask for a fresh one and they'll cook it up for you on the spot.

points_of_interest.name: Taiwan Restaurant
points_of_interest.description: Famous for their dumplings.

points_of_interest.name: Grand Cafe
points_of_interest.description: With 30-foot high ceilings supported by pillars, sunken tables, sculptures, and artwork adorning the walls, it's not hard to see that this place was once an elegant ballroom. Today it's an elegant dining room where they serve excellent French cuisine.
points_of_interest.hours: Breakfast: M-F 7AM-10:30AM; Brunch: Sa-Su 8AM-2:30PM; Lunch: M-F 11:30AM-2:30PM; Dinner: Su-Th 5PM-10PM, F-Sa 5PM-11PM

points_of_interest.name: Chowders
points_of_interest.description: Serving fresh seafood cocktails, clam chowder in a bread bowl, fish and chips, sandwiches, and salads. They also have a small "Not so Fishy... " menu for those who don't like seafood.

points_of_interest.name: Toy Boat Dessert Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Filled with vintage toys and a lively atmosphere, this fun restaurant serves ice cream, cakes, tortes, muffins and more. You can grab a breakfast or lunch there, but really just come for the treats.
