Over time a quiet residential neighborhood built up along the hillside, and their magnificent flowing gardens have always been something to admire on your way up or down. Other neighbors include a colony of colorful feral parrots, predominantly red-masked parakeets, which grew up as descendants of escaped domesticated pets. One can drive to the top, but it's better to take one of the narrow steps leading up and down the sides of the hill (including the Greenwich and Filbert Steps), as they offer better views over the Bay.

points_of_interest.name: Old Post Hospital
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1864, it displays Italianate and Greek Revival architectural styles. Constructed during the Civil War, it is one of the oldest standing buildings on the Presidio. The original structure was modified by adding wings and enclosing the porches. In 1897, an octagonal surgical tower with windows on all sides was added to provide a well-lit operating room.

points_of_interest.name: Filbert Steps
points_of_interest.description: The Filbert Steps are the part of Filbert Street that runs between Battery Street and Telegraph Hill Boulevard in North Beach. The steps end next to Coit Tower, and offer a scenic — though somewhat strenuous — route for visitors of the tower. In fact, following the steps is at times faster than driving to Coit Tower due to the high demand for relatively few parking spots near the site. Visitors of the steps will see public gardens, stylish homes and views of North Beach and the bay; if a path is not gated or specifically signed with "No Trespassing," then it is most likely public. Also, it pays to be adventurous: some of the best gardens and views are off the stairs. Finally, there is more than one way up and down; if you make a round trip you should find a new route for the return leg. Just avoid private property.

points_of_interest.name: Palace of Fine Arts
points_of_interest.description: The only structure remaining from the 1915 World's Fair, it features a classical Roman rotunda (1,100 feet wide, 162 feet high) with curved colonnades (30 Corinthian columns frame a wide walkway in the colonnade) situated in an idyllic park setting with a classical European-Style lagoon. It's a great place to unwind, have a picnic, and watch the swans float elegantly by. It also has a theater offering a variety of shows, musical and cultural events.

points_of_interest.name: Interfaith Center at the Presidio
points_of_interest.description: Built in the early 1930s, this cruciform-shaped sanctuary is a fine example of Spanish Colonial Revival style architecture, with features that embellished early mission churches. Stained glass windows depict virtues of military character, and a large wall mural by Victor Arnautoff (famed Coit Tower muralist) depicts the peacetime activities of the Army.

points_of_interest.name: Baker Beach
points_of_interest.description: A beautiful, immaculately kept 1-mile stretch of beach, set just behind the Golden Gate Bridge. Unfortunately, due to strong currents, the beach is not very safe for swimming, but for "land-lovers" it does have many outdoor barbeques and designated picnic areas to eat and relax at. Toward the northern end of the beach there is also an unofficial nude section that mainly seems to attract gay men. It has free parking and clean restrooms.

points_of_interest.name: Coastal Bluffs
points_of_interest.description: Beaches and rocky shoreline lie at the base of the coastal bluffs, while their tops provide expansive views of the Pacific coastline. The Coastal Trail extends along the wind-swept coastal bluffs, where some of the most intact natural habitat in the Presidio harbors rare plants adapted to serpentine soil and cool foggy conditions.

points_of_interest.name: Crissy Field Marsh and Beach
points_of_interest.description: Known by many names — "The city's front yard" and "The Golden Gate promenade" — this used to be one of the country's most active and strategic military airstrips. Today, under the care the Golden Gate National Parks Association, the 28 acre site has been transformed into recreational space for joggers, cyclists, walkers, and picnickers. There is also a significant project underway to return 18 acres back to its original tidal marshlands. With this effort, Crissy Field is fast becoming a great place to see local wildlife such as migrating long-billed curlews, semipalmated plovers and western sandpipers.

points_of_interest.name: El Polin Spring
points_of_interest.description: El Polin spring water bubbles from a rock wall at the head of this riparian valley. The spring provided a source of fresh water for the Spanish Presidio, and Spanish and Mexican families built their homes in this sheltered valley. Today, you can picnic in the bucolic meadows near the spring or explore the surrounding forest and grasslands.

points_of_interest.name: Inspiration Point
points_of_interest.description: Perched high atop the Presidio, Inspiration Point has great views over the Presidio and the Bay and is great to visit both during the day and at night.

points_of_interest.name: Lobos Creek Valley
points_of_interest.description: Contains the last free-flowing stream in San Francisco, which provides water to the inhabitants of the Presidio.

points_of_interest.name: Lovers' Lane
points_of_interest.description: One of the oldest foot trails in the Presidio, Lovers' Lane is an easy, one-mile walk. U.S. soldiers used the trail to visit their lovers and family in San Francisco.

points_of_interest.name: Mountain Lake
points_of_interest.description: The campsite of the Anza settlement party in 1776, it became a source of fresh water for San Francisco during the early years. Ducks and waterfowl make their home among the tule reeds. Mountain Lake today fronts a popular neighborhood park with playground equipment, tennis courts and a Par Course.

points_of_interest.name: Presidio Forest
points_of_interest.description: A mature forest of pine, cypress, eucalyptus and other non-native trees covers the higher areas of the Presidio. The army planted these trees from the 1880s through the 1940s in order to make the area appear larger with more relief, to limit visibility within the Presidio, and to beautify the post.

points_of_interest.name: Presidio Golf Course
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1895 by the private San Francisco Golf and Country Club, the original 9-hole Presidio Golf Course was one of the earliest courses on the West Coast. In 1910, the course was expanded to 18-holes. Today, the course is open to the general public.

points_of_interest.name: Presidio Tunnel Tops
points_of_interest.description: Gently sloping park and picnic area with views of the Golden Gate Bridge, San Francisco Bay, and downtown San Francisco, weather permitting. Includes playground and food trucks.

points_of_interest.name: Mountain Lake Park
points_of_interest.description: A small hiking trail winds around this scenic lake, noted for its historic importance in that it supplied water to the nearby colonial Spanish settlement of the Presidio. There is also a playground and a tennis court at the southern side of the lake.
points_of_interest.address: located just north of the intersection of Lake and Funston at the southern end of the Presidio park

points_of_interest.name: Golden Gate Bridge
points_of_interest.hours: Open 24 hours, occasionally closed Sunday morning for events. Welcome Center: daily, 9AM-6PM

points_of_interest.name: Joseph Strauss Legacy Circle
points_of_interest.description: Joseph B. Strauss Memorial Sculpture of bridge architect Joseph B. Strauss.

points_of_interest.name: The Six Gallery
points_of_interest.description: On Friday, October 7, 1955, the ''"Six Gallery reading"'' took place here. It was a seminal moment in the Beat Generation movement and attracted such poets and writers as Alan Ginsberg, Gary Snyder, Philip Lamantia, Michael McClure, Philip Whalen, and Jack Kerouac. The gallery has since closed but you can still visit the site where this watershed event took place.

points_of_interest.name: Wave Organ
points_of_interest.description: Designed by George Gonzales and Peter Richards in 1986, the Wave Organ is a system of PVC pipes that harness the power of the ocean to create music... or at least what can be interpreted as music! There is a unique space at the end of a spit of land where you can sit and enjoy the sounds, and even if it's not your kind of music, there are some excellent views and it's also a great place to relax and have a picnic.
points_of_interest.address: at the end of Yacht Rd

points_of_interest.name: Yacht Clubs
points_of_interest.description: You can't come to the Marina district without actually seeing, well... the marina! Here where you will find an impressive flotilla of vessels — both sail and power. There are various "small craft" harbors located at either end of Marina Green, but the two main yacht clubs are:

points_of_interest.name: Golden Gate Yacht Club
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1939, this club is both a popular destination for pleasure cruises and for competitive regatta racing. It's plainer than its neighbor the SFYC, however it got a major boost of late when Larry Ellison and the Oracle guys signed up and the club became the challenge club of record for the America's Cup.

points_of_interest.name: St Francis Yacht Club
points_of_interest.description: Founded in 1927, this club has over 2,400 members and is also popular as both a cruise and regatta venue. It is reputedly the most exclusive yacht club in San Francisco and there are some serious vessels docked here.

points_of_interest.name: Alemany Farmers Market
points_of_interest.description: Forget the farmers market at the Ferry Building, unless you just can't live without the high prices and the most fashionable vegetables. San Francisco's original 1943 farmer's market is where it's at. It was founded by the Victory Garden Council as a WWII ag-surplus depot! Rock-bottom cheap, we-picked-it-at-3AM fresh, it's where elderly Asian ladies swarm piles of fresh peanuts and carefully pick out the live chicken to bring home. It has flowers at unbelievable prices and a really stellar selection of basic fruits, nuts, tubers and vegetables, and exotic Asian produce. There aren't that many organic farmers, but there are some. Get there early for salad greens and Euro-American vegetables, as these go fast. The fish market is mixed but sometimes has good local catches.

points_of_interest.name: Good Life Grocery
points_of_interest.description: People tend to have a love-hate relationship with this grocery store on the busy Cortland/Andover corner. On one hand, it's a fine, manageably-sized market with all the quality brands of pasta, meat, dairy, condiments, juices, vegetarian staples, etc. that you would hope for in a neighborhood with a significant upscale, foodie population. On the other hand, the prices are high, and it would be really nice to be able to purchase a razor blade or non-natural hair conditioner. Great wine selection and recommendations, though.

points_of_interest.name: Cliff's Variety
points_of_interest.description: Toys, gifts, kitchenware, hardware, and the newly remodeled annex next door is where to shop for do it yourself home decor items and is THE place to get rhinestones.

points_of_interest.name: ImagiKnit
points_of_interest.description: These women opened up the yarn shop that they'd like to hang out in and the whole neighborhood concurs that they're doing it right.

points_of_interest.name: Noe Valley Farmers Market
points_of_interest.description: Year-round California-certified farmers market.

points_of_interest.name: Just For Fun & Scribbledoodles
points_of_interest.description: Stationery and gifts; custom color printing and calligraphy for announcements. They have also opened an art supply store across the street.

points_of_interest.name: Argonaut Book Shop
points_of_interest.description: The bookshelves here are any war buff's haven, with a treasure trove of books on the history of California and the American West. It also has good collections on the American Civil War, American railroads, regional Americana, antiques and maritime books.

points_of_interest.name: Atelier Des Modistes
points_of_interest.description: Bridal gowns and jewelry.

points_of_interest.name: Miraloma Market
points_of_interest.description: Neighborhood convenience store that also sells lottery tickets; its also home to the Miraloma Tacqueria.

points_of_interest.name: Cris
points_of_interest.description: A consignment shop with high-end goods.

points_of_interest.name: Soko Hardware
points_of_interest.description: Has everything from copper rain chains and iron cabinetry findings, fine woodworking tools to bulk nails, porcelain to everyday kitchenware; just what you want in a longstanding hardware store.

points_of_interest.name: 826 Valencia
points_of_interest.description: The Pirate Store The majority of this space is dedicated to children's writing workshops. The front, however, is a cheeky store selling all things pirate. Not to be missed. Founded by McSweeney's Dave Eggers.

points_of_interest.name: Mollie Stones Tower Market
points_of_interest.description: Boutique market with butcher and deli departments

points_of_interest.name: Molte Cose
points_of_interest.description: "Molte Cose", or "many things" in Italian, fits the name of this shop. Tons of cool adornments, clothes and accessories.

points_of_interest.name: Maido Stationery
points_of_interest.description: Has a huge collection of washii decorative papers that is only surpassed by their incredible collection of pens, stationery and gift items.

points_of_interest.name: Aldea Home + Baby
points_of_interest.description: A design-minded shop with a wide array of lifestyle accessories, bed and bath products and dining accouterments. It's also a shop that caters to all of your baby needs, with stylish clothing, hand-picked toys, and unique, modern furnishings.

points_of_interest.name: Stonestown Galleria Shopping Center
points_of_interest.description: Shopping mall next to SFSU. Anchor stores are Nordstrom, Macy's, Williams-Sonoma, Borders, J. Crew, Ann Taylor, Banana Republic, and an Apple Computer store.

points_of_interest.name: Velvet da Vinci
points_of_interest.description: Established in 1991, the gallery shows contemporary jewelry by international artists and craft-based sculpture. Housed in an old furniture factory the gallery has 10 exhibitions a year and is a must see for fans of cutting-edge jewelry.

points_of_interest.name: Kinokuniya Bookstore
points_of_interest.description: If you're into Japanese books, magazines, or comic books (otherwise known as manga), then this is your place to be. The only San Francisco branch of the famous Japanese chain, Kinokuniya carries thousands of titles, including dozens in English. So a crash course in Japanese is not essential to shop here.

points_of_interest.name: Dog Eared Books
points_of_interest.description: A great selection of used books and readings by authors.

points_of_interest.name: Vino!
points_of_interest.description: They have a great selection of wines (circa 300 varieties) to suit every budget.

points_of_interest.name: Gump's
points_of_interest.description: San Francisco's source of luxury housewares, from couches to crystal. Though famous names like Waterford appear on the shelves, the selection emphasizes home furnishings as art, often with an elegant Asian feel. The dominant style is not quite modernist but hardly middle-American traditional. It's difficult to do justice to a native's feelings toward Gump's without sounding like a bad marketing piece. This is the "look" that says one's parents and grandparents went to the right private schools. If your home looks like Gump's, you've not only "arrived"—you've been here longer than just about anyone else. As well as housewares, Gump's sells jewelry, holiday decor, and the odd bit of upscale soap.

points_of_interest.name: Britex
points_of_interest.description: Arguably the largest fabric store on the west coast, filling four floors of a narrow building. Don't look for calicos for your quilting project: this is the land of luxury fabrics for faking couture at home. If you've ever wanted to make a cheap sweater look expensive by adding deluxe buttons, head straight for the third floor, where 30,000 styles await your approval (don't even think of touching a button - the clerks do that). Britex is also notable for selling remnants that are big enough for a real project.

points_of_interest.name: Williams Sonoma
points_of_interest.description: The Union Square store is the flagship store of this international chain, and it's a cathedral to the gracious kitchen. Acres of housewares gleam beneath twin spiral stairs that lead to the land of crystal and tablecloths. This isn't your mother's mall-store Williams Sonoma. There are usually pretty good free samples being passed out, too.

points_of_interest.name: Amoeba Music
points_of_interest.description: The best place in San Francisco to buy vinyl and cds, new and used, with an emphasis on indie music. It has one of the largest selections for an indie music store in the country.

points_of_interest.name: Thomas Pink
points_of_interest.description: This place might seem obsessed with its eponymous color, if you judge by the store displays, but the upscale clothier also knows about white, beige, blue, and yellow.

points_of_interest.name: Booksmith
points_of_interest.description: An independent bookstore that's been around since the 1970s, this bookstore is best known for its events program, with many book signings from famous and honored authors.

points_of_interest.name: Wilkes Bashford
points_of_interest.description: This is just the place to pop in for a $1,000 jacket, a $500 cashmere sweater, or those delicious Jimmy Choo shoes. Every now and again, there is a major sale on the top floor. You don't need to watch for the sales banners -- just notice when the crowds mobbing into the store look suspiciously like the same people who bussed your table the night before.

points_of_interest.name: Life
points_of_interest.description: Exotic perfumes and aromatherapy oils, incense, bath beads, jewelry, purses, cards, and vaguely east Indian themed goods. Get some henna painted on your hands in the henna lounge.

points_of_interest.name: San Francisco Art Exchange
points_of_interest.description: This is a gallery for those interested in rock paintings and photographs, and they also sport a large Beatles collection and paintings by Ronnie Wood and Alberto Vargas. A must for music enthusiasts, if you have the budget.

points_of_interest.name: Roberts Hardware
points_of_interest.description: A non-chain hardware store with over 20,000 items in inventory and another 200,000 available by special order. The oldest family-owned store on Haight Street, celebrating 75 years in 2006. Staffed by knowledgeable, friendly workers who are willing to take the time to explain how to make your repairs without any of the condescension or attitude found in other stores.

points_of_interest.name: Alexander Book Co.
points_of_interest.description: A large independent bookstore with three floors of thousands of new books.

points_of_interest.name: Gamescape
points_of_interest.description: Tabletop games, of pretty much every type and genre. Regularly hosts in-store gameplay events.

points_of_interest.name: General Bead
points_of_interest.description: Thousands of beads and bead-based products for any bead and jewelry lover.

points_of_interest.name: Metreon
points_of_interest.description: This mall/entertainment complex has some interesting shops and a 15-screen movie theater with an IMAX screen. A food court on the lower level serves the convention area and is overwhelmed during lunch hours of the major conventions. The space is next to Target.

points_of_interest.name: Podesta Baldocchi
points_of_interest.description: A charming and long-standing floral shop.

points_of_interest.name: Rincon Center
points_of_interest.description: This is mostly for dining but there are also many shops here as well.

points_of_interest.name: Westfield San Francisco Centre
points_of_interest.description: This massive nine-floor Westfield-owned complex contains around 400 shops and restaurants, including some upscale places. Anchors for the mall include a Bloomingdale's, a Nordstorm, a Bristol Farms grocery, and a movie theater.

points_of_interest.name: 6th Avenue Aquarium
points_of_interest.description: Small store selling aquarium supplies and fishes, but its small scale beats many public exhibits for fun and colorful fish.

points_of_interest.name: Amazing Fantasy
points_of_interest.description: A comic book store, owned by a guy named Frank. Friendly staff. They have a small collection of back issues, and will order anything for you by request.

points_of_interest.name: Green Apple Books & Music
points_of_interest.description: Renowned independent book and record store dating back to before the Beat Era. Both used and new books.

points_of_interest.name: Mollusk Surf Shop
points_of_interest.description: Cheery local shop with easy to wear California clothes, colorful surf boards and surf gear, and an art gallery. Sometimes they host fun music shows and art opening parties. Medium pricing.

points_of_interest.name: Blackbird Bookstore and Cafe
points_of_interest.description: Cafe and bookshop with a patio in the back. Highly curated book selection and lots of gift options. Great for kids.

points_of_interest.name: Kayo Books
points_of_interest.description: "Specializing in vintage collectible paperbacks from the 1940s to 1970s and esoteric books of all persuasions... " They have a large stock of rare and out of print books, many of which are of the lurid and sleazy persuasion.

points_of_interest.name: Napa Valley Winery Exchange
points_of_interest.description: Well known wine store featuring hard to get and small production wines.

points_of_interest.name: San Francisco Antique and Artisans Market
points_of_interest.description: Three times a week, over 100 vendors come together to sell antiques, gifts, and keepsakes from all over the world. Appropriately, the market is held at UN Plaza.

points_of_interest.name: The Anchorage Shopping Center
points_of_interest.description: Covering just one square block in Fisherman's Wharf, there are over 30 specialty shops and restaurants here.

points_of_interest.name: Chinese Bookmarks
points_of_interest.description: Tired of the same old souvenir stores? Looking for a more authentic souvenir? Down Ross Alley you'll sometimes find an old Chinese man in a doorway, who for a few dollars, will inscribe your name in Chinese onto a handcrafted bookmark.
points_of_interest.hours: Hours : Vary (Sometimes he's there, sometimes he's not!)

points_of_interest.name: North Point Shopping Center
points_of_interest.description: Less touristy, and set back a few blocks from the actual Wharf, this shopping center contains 15 shops, including a Safeway supermarket, Walgreens drug store, GNC, and Radio Shack, as well as services such as ATMs and a 24-hour fitness center.

points_of_interest.name: China Station
points_of_interest.description: If you like reasonably priced souvenirs, this is the place for you. They have a very broad selection, selling everything from Chinese exercise balls to Buddha statues.

points_of_interest.name: Dragon House
points_of_interest.description: Sells genuine antiques and fine art from China, Japan, Tibet and Mongolia.

points_of_interest.name: Peking Bazaar
points_of_interest.description: Huge sprawling store selling a wide range of discount imported goods from Asia including lanterns, candles, sarongs, silk kimono, geisha outfits and Chinese dolls.

points_of_interest.name: A. Cavalli & Co
points_of_interest.description: This shop with its friendly proprietor sells everything Italian, from ornate imported espresso and pasta makers to Italian newspapers, magazines, CDs, and DVDs.

points_of_interest.name: Biordi Arts
points_of_interest.description: For 50 years the owners have been selling imprinted Renaissance style Italian Majolica as well as Italian Hand painted Dinnerware.

points_of_interest.name: Goorin Brothers Hat Makers
points_of_interest.description: These guys are determined to bring hats back in a big way. Along the way they've had many famous customers including Tom Cruise and JayZ. How big is your head?

points_of_interest.name: Ambiance
points_of_interest.description: The store has a great selection of women's clothes and jewelry.

points_of_interest.name: Blu
points_of_interest.description: Women's modern European clothes and accessories store.

points_of_interest.name: Books Inc
points_of_interest.description: Unusual and quirky book store that holds a storytelling hour for kids every Sunday afternoon.

points_of_interest.name: Gallery of Jewels
points_of_interest.description: This gallery sells distinctive, limited edition jewelry handcrafted by local and international designers. They have a good variety of silver, gold and platinum accessories and sell jewelry for both men and women.

points_of_interest.name: Golden Gate Bridge Gift Center
points_of_interest.description: You can purchase souvenirs of the Golden Gate Bridge here.

points_of_interest.name: Margaret O'Leary
points_of_interest.description: Ladies store specializing in high-end knits and accessories.

points_of_interest.name: Nest
points_of_interest.description: French-inspired furniture, gifts, and accessories.

points_of_interest.name: Past Perfect
points_of_interest.description: Antique store with a large and eclectic selection of vintage goods and artwork to choose from.

points_of_interest.name: Safeway
points_of_interest.description: Large Safeway grocery store on the Marina.

points_of_interest.name: Parker House
points_of_interest.description: A gay owned and operated hotel in a very pretty old building.

points_of_interest.name: Twin Peaks Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Not the Ritz but a cheap budget hotel option

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Mithila
points_of_interest.description: Established in 1920, this is a relatively clean hotel and reasonably priced.

points_of_interest.name: Cornell Hotel De France
points_of_interest.description: A small and historic hotel with a French theme.

points_of_interest.name: Golden Gate Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A charming budget hotel in an old Victorian.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn Golden Gateway Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A Holiday Inn with more amenities than the typical location and nice views of the city.

points_of_interest.name: Columbus Motor Inn
points_of_interest.description: The Columbus Motor Inn is in the nice part of North Beach, on the border of the Fishermen's Wharf district, within easy walking distance of all Fisherman's Wharf attractions, and from Washington Square. Public transportation is very convenient, with the No. 30 bus stopping at the door, and the Bay and Taylor Cable Car Turntable a short walk away. Rooms are spacious, with good views and balconies on most Columbus Side rooms. Parking is limited, but covered: the first two floors of the building are parking, with all guest rooms above. No on-site food, but nearby restaurants cater to every budget and taste.

points_of_interest.name: Hayes Valley Inn
points_of_interest.description: European Style. Extremely cute, homey, and comfortable.

points_of_interest.name: Fairmont Hotel
points_of_interest.description: One of the most famous hotels in the city, having been gutted in the 1906 earthquake and fire, and rebuilt. The lobby is fantastic, and many rooms have fantastic views.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Kabuki
points_of_interest.description: A Japanese-style hotel with a calm ambiance.

points_of_interest.name: Huntington Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A former apartment building-turned-luxury hotel with individually decorated rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Queen Anne Hotel
points_of_interest.description: The Queen Anne provides a real San Francisco experience, being an 1890 Victorian Hotel between Pacific Heights and the Civic Center, and near Japantown. Some rooms have fireplaces, and afternoon tea is served daily.

points_of_interest.name: Intercontinental Mark Hopkins
points_of_interest.description: Historic hotel atop Nob Hill. Convenient for walking tours of the city.

points_of_interest.name: Inn At The Opera
points_of_interest.description: This hotel has 29 guestrooms and 18 suites which are individually decorated. It is situated in an excellent location.

points_of_interest.name: Petite Auberge
points_of_interest.description: A French provincial style inn. Cozy parlor with fireplace, afternoon wine and hors d'oeuvres. Many of the 26 guestrooms offer fireplaces. Breakfast buffet each morning.

points_of_interest.name: Hostelling International-Downtown
points_of_interest.description: Clean, cheap, safe and fun.

points_of_interest.name: Stanford Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Another 4-star hotel with marble baths and free limousine service.

points_of_interest.name: Pacific Tradewinds Backpackers
points_of_interest.description: The highest rated and smallest hostel in San Francisco. On the edge of Chinatown and the Financial District. Friendly, clean, modern and safe. Free internet.

points_of_interest.name: White Swan Inn
points_of_interest.description: A lovely small hotel with a fireplace in all 26 guestrooms. Dark wood paneling, floral carpets, comfy furniture, and English art and collectibles set the tone. Evening turndown service, breakfast buffet, and evening wine and hors d'oeuvres served fireside.

points_of_interest.name: The Donatello
points_of_interest.description: 94 deluxe rooms, the most spacious accommodations in San Francisco. Elegantly decorated with original Italian art, Travertine marble, Venetian glass and European antiques.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Vertigo
points_of_interest.description: A hotel with lots of bright colors and relatively few amenities compared to other splurge hotels in the area, but with nice rooms and a friendly staff.

points_of_interest.name: Handlery Union Square Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A family hotel with a European flair, and the feel of upscale boutique accommodations providing warm, personal attention. The cable car is located at the corner and attractions are within walking distance.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Abri
points_of_interest.description: No pool or free breakfast. Rooms are small but has everything you need for a reasonable price. The cable car, MUNI and BART stations are within walking distance.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel des Arts
points_of_interest.description: The hotel displays the work of contemporary local artists.

points_of_interest.name: Chancellor Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A classic hotel overlooking Powell Street. Offers a menu of pillow options for your sleeping comfort.

points_of_interest.name: The Clift Royal Sonesta Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Hotel features the Redwood Room restaurant, Fredericks for coffee and breakfast, private apartments, penthouse suites and meeting facilities.

points_of_interest.name: Galleria Park Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A boutique hotel with a half-acre private urban park. Good linens, flat-screen TVs and complimentary wine hour.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton San Francisco Financial District
points_of_interest.description: Situated at the nexus of Chinatown, North Beach and the Financial District, this 27 story hotel has some stunning views over the city and of San Francisco Bay.

points_of_interest.name: Mosser Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Nice, clean hotel with small rooms but a great location.

points_of_interest.name: Hilton San Francisco Union Square
points_of_interest.description: At 46 stories tall, this hotel is the tallest hotel in the downtown area and has excellent views over the city. It also has a heated outdoor swimming pool and jacuzzi, as well as high-speed internet in all rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Pickwick Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A historic hotel with very nice guestrooms and flexible meeting space.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Diva
points_of_interest.description: Sleek, modern boutique hotel just off Union Square. This place is pretty hip! It's also a non-smoking hotel.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Whitcomb
points_of_interest.description: This is a 460 room historic boutique hotel. An elegant, opulent building, it was first used as a temporary city hall after the 1906 earthquake. Italian marble, Austrian chandeliers, and a short walk to the Symphony/Opera and the Asian Art Museum. It also has a piano bar/wine bar.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Nikko
points_of_interest.description: Swanky large hotel with a boutique feel and very large bathrooms. Rooms are equipped with high-speed Internet, stereos and large flat panel televisions, and you can ask for the few rooms with Japanese style amenities. There is also an indoor fifteen-meter heated pool, whirlpool and a 24h gym. Hotel dining includes restaurant [http://www.restaurantanzu.com ANZU], which serves fresh sushi and excellent steaks. Also located inside the hotel's lobby is the [http://www.therrazzroom.com Rrazz Room Theater], with nightly cabaret and R&B and the Imperial Club rooms on the top floors provide some great views of the city.

points_of_interest.name: The Clancy
points_of_interest.description: Marriot Autograph Collection A Marriot with all the amenities that generally come with it.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Emblem San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: formerly Hotel Rex The Hotel Rex, now the Hotel Emblem, was inspired by the San Francisco art and literary salons of the 1920s and 30s. The clubby lobby surrounds guests with distinctive period furnishings, walls of antiquarian books, and a collection of exotic objects, original portraits and murals.

points_of_interest.name: Four Seasons Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Very high-end hotel. Beautiful art collection, and extensive sports club with fitness facilities and spa.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Vitale
points_of_interest.description: Great boutique hotel, right on the waterfront, across from the historic Ferry Building. Rooms with city or bay views, rooftop day-spa, and a restaurant and bar with outside terrace seating.

points_of_interest.name: Harbor Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A waterfront boutique hotel on the Embarcadero, across from the San Francisco Ferry Building, with views onto San Francisco Bay.

points_of_interest.name: The Inn San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: An old Victorian house converted into a bed and breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: Hyatt Regency San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: A very prominent hotel near the waterfront, with many rooms having lovely views of the Bay. Typically of Hyatts, there are plenty of amenities and very nice rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Griffon
points_of_interest.description: A comparatively smaller hotel with small but very comfy rooms and good service.

points_of_interest.name: 1906 Mission
points_of_interest.description: A hostel/B&B with private double and queen bedrooms, all with shared bathrooms. Very clean and quiet. The bathrooms feel positively luxurious with piles of fresh towels, toiletries and wooden finishes. Breakfast included.

points_of_interest.name: JW Marriott
points_of_interest.description: former Pan Pacific A AAA four-diamond hotel with lots of amenities and nice rooms.

points_of_interest.name: InterContinental Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A translucent cool-blue tower that doubles as a city landmark.

points_of_interest.name: St. Francis House
points_of_interest.description: An urban Anglican convent with a guest apartment on the street level which opens onto a surprisingly quiet flower and vegetable garden. Separate entrance, kitchen, bathroom, living room, and a double bed and a single bed in the bedroom. Free internet access and TV with basic cable. Limited on-street parking is available in the neighborhood. Open for guests for short periods of time (normally 2 weeks or less). Kitchen is equipped for self-catering with breakfast items furnished in the apartment.

points_of_interest.name: Le Méridien
points_of_interest.description: formerly the Park Hyatt A luxury hotel that mostly caters to business travelers. Large rooms and very nice furnishings and art work. If you stay at this hotel, make a point not to eat breakfast here, as it is expensive and there are other good options nearby.

points_of_interest.name: Marriott Marquis
points_of_interest.description: Convention center hotel across the street from the Moscone Center.

points_of_interest.name: Mandarin Oriental
points_of_interest.description: A 150-room hotel on the top eleven floors of the First Interstate Center, the third tallest building in the city of San Francisco. The view from the rooms are exceptional, with floor to ceiling windows and great views.

points_of_interest.name: The Palace Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Established in 1875, the Palace has 552 guest rooms. In 1945, the official banquet honoring the opening session of the United Nations was held in The Garden Court at The Palace.

points_of_interest.name: Marines' Memorial Club & Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A historic hotel with some elegantly appointed rooms and suites. Fine dining at the Leatherneck Steakhouse & Lounge and performances at the historical Marines' Memorial Theatre on the premises.

points_of_interest.name: Metro Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A reasonably priced hotel just one block north of Haight Street. The rooms are quite basic, but functional, clean, and quite inexpensive for the central city. There is an excellent French restaurant downstairs, with outdoor dining and weekend brunch. Rooms directly over Divisadero Street can be quite loud on the weekends.

points_of_interest.name: St. Regis Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A historic and very upscale hotel with a spa, butler service, and on-site restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Marriott Union Square
points_of_interest.description: A trendy San Francisco boutique hotel. Formerly the Hotel 480, this hotel has been completely renovated to become a Marriott.

points_of_interest.name: Red Victorian Bed & Breakfast
points_of_interest.description: A throwback to the Haight-Ashbury's glory days during the 1960s, this peace and love themed B&B has several eclectically themed rooms and suites, as well as a cafe downstairs.

points_of_interest.name: W Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Another major convention center hotel, with lots of amenities and very nice rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Omni San Francisco Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A luxury hotel with marble floors and wood paneling in the lobby and very nice rooms.

points_of_interest.name: The Orchard Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A stylish 'green' boutique hotel with beautiful rooms and suites, as well as meeting space, a fitness center, and on-site dining - Daffodil Restaurant.

points_of_interest.name: Parc 55 San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: A highrise hotel with large rooms, lots of amenities, and great views of Downtown.

points_of_interest.name: Beacon Grand
points_of_interest.description: A historic (built in 1928) and rather lavish hotel a block up the street from Union Square. Formerly known as the Sir Francis Drake Hotel, it changed its name in 2022 due to Drake's involvement in the slave trade.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Triton
points_of_interest.description: Located just outside Chinatown, directly across from the south gate. Trendy, modern, and a little pricey. But the rooms are nicely appointed, and they offer a free tasting of local wines every afternoon.

points_of_interest.name: Villa Florence
points_of_interest.description: Has the feel of an Italian-inspired hotel. Amenities include an onsite bar, Kuleto's Italian Restaurant, a fitness center and a sundry area.

points_of_interest.name: Westin-St Francis Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Now a member of the Westin chain, this is an iconic San Francisco hotel. The lavish lobby and cafe area are used as a meeting place by quite a lot of people who aren't guests there, despite the pricey lattes and ritzy atmosphere. In a peculiar bit of design, the lobby has a side entrance to the Harry & David store, should you need to pop over for a few chocolate-covered cranberries. A ride on the exterior glass elevators offers a splendid view of the skyline, and can be done even if you're not staying. Although the St. Francis has a reputation for being pricy, it runs off-season specials.

points_of_interest.name: Adelaide Hostel
points_of_interest.description: This is a popular backpacker hostel just two blocks from [[San Francisco/Union Square-Financial District|Union Square]].

points_of_interest.name: Axiom Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Along with a restaurant, this smoke-free hotel has a 24-hour fitness center and a bar/lounge. WiFi in public areas is free. Other amenities include a coffee shop/café, valet parking, and coffee/tea in a common area.

points_of_interest.name: Hostelling International-City Center
points_of_interest.description: Clean, cheap, safe, fun. The hostel has 75 beds in total, some are 4 or 5 bed dorms and others private rooms. All rooms have their own private bathroom. They offer a free breakfast and free wi-fi.

points_of_interest.name: BEI Hotel San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: Stay in the heart of the city and enjoy a gym, well-appointed guest rooms, parking on-site, and more. Dog friendly.

points_of_interest.name: The Opal San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: An elegant 5 story hotel that was built after the 1906 earthquake, it has 164 guest rooms. They have a gym, laundry facilities, and all access to free wi-fi.

points_of_interest.name: Rodeway Inn Civic Center
points_of_interest.description: This is a pretty standard but comfortable inn near Van Ness. They offer some free limited parking and a complimentary breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: Taylor Hotel
points_of_interest.description: This is an older building and the rooms are in need of paint, but it's relatively clean. There is a nice Indian couple who runs the place, they have wireless internet and a community computer in the lobby and a continental breakfast each morning. It's in a great location, just 2 blocks from [[San Francisco/Union Square-Financial District|Union Square]].

points_of_interest.name: USA Hostels San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: Great hostel operating in two buildings just off Union Square. All rooms have their own bathrooms.

points_of_interest.name: Wharf Inn
points_of_interest.description: Small, friendly, and in the heart of Fisherman's Wharf. It has free parking.

points_of_interest.name: Cova Hotel
points_of_interest.description: This hotel has 96 well decorated rooms in the heart of downtown. All rooms have 300 thread count sheets, high definition TVs, complimentary breakfast, and free wi-fi.

points_of_interest.name: Courtyard Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: Part of the Marriott group, this non-smoking, four-story hotel is 2 blocks from Ghirardelli Square.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Bijou
points_of_interest.description: Hotel Bijou is inspired by San Francisco's rich cinematic history, adorned with movie palace stylings and Hollywood portraits, and features a mini movie theater in the lobby.

points_of_interest.name: Holiday Inn Express — Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: One of the better rated hotels on the Wharf.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Metropolis
points_of_interest.description: It's on the eastern outskirts of the Tenderloin, but there can be people sleeping in stairways and panhandling right next to the hotel, so it's authentic enough. Inside it is perfectly clean.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Caza
points_of_interest.description: Located in the midst of the popular tourist area, this kid-friendly hotel caters to tourists and families and offers amenities that include foosball, a pool table, grab & go snacks, and a bar.

points_of_interest.name: The Phoenix Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A boutique hotel, favored by musicians of all stripes, with free parking and breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: Suites at Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: The Suites is a small (24 suites) but comfortable and modern hotel that offers one or two-bedroom floor plans with many amenities.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Carlton
points_of_interest.description: A reasonably-priced boutique hotel with decorations that feature international travel. Non-smoking and pet-friendly hotel, and certified as a green business. Saha Restaurant in the lobby serves Arabic fusion cuisine.

points_of_interest.name: Argonaut Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A high-end luxury boutique hotel overlooking the bay and very centrally located on the Wharf. Ask for a room away from the front if you mind noise. It's a 100% smoke-free environment.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Adagio
points_of_interest.description: A luxury boutique hotel featuring a fresh design that bridges its Spanish Colonial Revival architectural roots to a clean and contemporary design aesthetic. 2½ blocks away from the Powell St Cable Car line, 6 blocks from the Moscone Convention Center.

points_of_interest.name: Hyatt Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: Modern hotel with full-service and clean and comfortable rooms.

points_of_interest.name: The Hotel Monaco
points_of_interest.description: A fun and hip boutique hotel. This is part of Kimpton Hotels, a San Francisco based hotel and restaurant company.

points_of_interest.name: Marriott Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: 285 rooms and 11 suites.

points_of_interest.name: Serrano Hotel
points_of_interest.description: This is a deluxe boutique hotel in a 17-story Spanish Revival building. They have free high speed internet and a wine appreciation hour every evening.

points_of_interest.name: Riu Fisherman's Wharf
points_of_interest.description: Amenities include a gym, heated swimming pool, and conference rooms.

points_of_interest.name: Geary Parkway Motel
points_of_interest.description: This former dive has been completely remodeled with clean rooms, nice televisions, microwaves, blowdryers, irons, and mini fridges. Reasonable prices, safe and neat - the owners have put a lot of effort into making this motel quiet and nice.

points_of_interest.name: Seal Rock Inn
points_of_interest.description: Nestled at the westernmost edge of the city overlooking The Cliff House and The Sutro Baths' ruins, this hotel has a small pool, volleyball court, and restaurant. You're a bit out of the way from downtown (about a 30 minute drive/bus), but a great location for someone who enjoys San Francisco's nature, or who will be heading to Marin or down to the peninsula, as you are on the other side of most of the clogged commuting routes.

points_of_interest.name: Ocean Park Motel
points_of_interest.description: 1930s 'Art Deco' motel. Just a short stroll to the beach and San Francisco Zoo.

points_of_interest.name: Grant Plaza Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Good for 1 or 2 night stay. Rates are reasonable. Make sure you ask for one of the outside rooms that overlook Grant Avenue, the inside rooms are small, dark and dingy. Close to parking garages and walking distance to many restaurants, bars and attractions. Staff is friendly.

points_of_interest.name: The Green Tortoise Hostel
points_of_interest.description: A favorite of backpackers world-wide, price includes free internet and wi-fi, free breakfast every morning, a sauna, pool table, common room, free beer at the Beer Olympics on Tuesday nights and free live music on Sundays. An ideal location, right between Chinatown and North Beach and a short walk from downtown.

points_of_interest.name: San Remo Hotel
points_of_interest.description: At the other end of the spectrum is the San Remo Hotel,  All rooms except a rooftop suite are under $100. It was built right after the 1906 earthquake, became apartments later, and has been nicely reconverted to a hotel. It appears to be a favorite place for European tourists. It is quiet, all non-smoking, has no room phones nor TVs, and shared baths.  A nice and large Italian restaurant, Fior d`Italia, self-proclaimed "The oldest Italian restaurant in the United States," has moved into its street floor.

points_of_interest.name: Castro Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Fancy a short stay at an S.R.O., well here's one that rents by the week.  The rooms are clean, it's in the heart of North Beach, it's safe — being directly opposite the police station, and it gets good reviews.

points_of_interest.name: SW Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Named after its owner Sam Wong, this budget hotel is decorated with everything Asian.  The rooms are a bit smaller than standard but it is situated in a very central location in Chinatown and the price is reasonable.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Boheme
points_of_interest.description: Hotel Boheme is located in a popular Italian neighborhood with decorations that pay tribute to San Francisco's Beat Generation.  The building may be hard to find, with only a single innocuous doorway covered by a small awning.  You have to buzz at the door to enter but you get a key for this door on check in. Past the door is a steep and narrow staircase leading up to the next floor. On the second floor to the right of the landing is the hotel office. A bottle of Sherry surrounded by cordial glasses is set out for guests on the landing sideboard each night. Hotel staff are always friendly, helpful and knowledgeable about everything San Francisco.

points_of_interest.name: The Orchard Garden Hotel
points_of_interest.description: A stylish eco-friendly hotel, claiming to be San Francisco's "greenest" hotel, this lodging gets almost universally good reviews.

points_of_interest.name: Ritz-Carlton San Francisco
points_of_interest.description: This hotel has a spacious lounge, fitness center, pool, and 4 star dining room in a Beaux-Arts building. It has 336 guestrooms, including 60 suites.

points_of_interest.name: Washington Square Inn
points_of_interest.description: Modeled after boutique European hotels it offers many services including a complimentary breakfast, and evening hors d'oeuvres. Rooms are well appointed with European antiques, cable TV, private baths, and free wi-fi. Centrally located in North Beach, it has views over Russian Hill, Telegraph Hill, and Washington Square Park.

points_of_interest.name: Greenwich Inn
points_of_interest.description: Budget hotel with free parking one block from Union St. It has 32 renovated guest rooms and offers an in-room coffee service and a complimentary newspaper daily.

points_of_interest.name: Hostelling International-Fisherman's Wharf Hostel
points_of_interest.description: Even if you're unsure about hostels, you should still consider this place; the location alone makes it worth your while, as it is in a park-like setting with great views of the Golden Gate Bridge and Alcatraz and is within easy walking distance of [[San Francisco/Fisherman's Wharf|Fisherman's Wharf]]. It has a total of 150 Beds in dormitory style rooms. Quite clean and safe, with wi-fi, laundry facilities, lockers, and free breakfast.

points_of_interest.name: Buena Vista Motor Inn
points_of_interest.description: Another standard motor inn, this one offers free parking and a complimentary continental breakfast to get you going in the morning.

points_of_interest.name: Chelsea Motor Inn
points_of_interest.description: Features an English Tudor style building with an antique roof. Clean, good quality rooms at a reasonable price. Nothing too special, but it is centrally located.

points_of_interest.name: Cow Hollow Motor Inn & Suites
points_of_interest.description: Centrally located in the Cow Hollow neighborhood, this motel offers 112 standard and reasonably priced rooms. The decor is definitely dated and will not suit everyone — they have floral wallpaper that might just keep you up at night! However, the rooms are comfortable and they do offer free parking.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel del Sol
points_of_interest.description: Voted CitySearch San Francisco's "Best Budget Hotel", "Best Family-Friendly Hotel," and "Best Hotel Pool" in 2006. Part of the fancy Joie de Vivre hotel group, this formerly nondescript motor lodge was rejuvenated with some cool colors, interior design, and upgraded management.

points_of_interest.name: La Luna Inn
points_of_interest.description: A rejuvenated 1960s Motor Inn. The bespoke furniture and colorful decor creates a bright, fun, and fanciful atmosphere here.

points_of_interest.name: Laurel Inn
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1963, this renovated hotel has a comfortable yet fashionable interior. Each room is spacious and similar in size to a studio apartment with some even having kitchenettes.

points_of_interest.name: Marina Inn
points_of_interest.description: Comfortable and traditional style inn with a quiet B&B atmosphere. They have 40 guest rooms and offer complimentary continental breakfast and free newspapers.

points_of_interest.name: Marina Motel
points_of_interest.description: Classic motor inn with a Mediterranean flavor — flower boxes fragrance the quaint European style rooms. They offer free wi-fi, free parking, and complimentary in room coffee.

points_of_interest.name: Motel Capri
points_of_interest.description: This is a small family run motel with just 46 guest rooms. Thankfully, this one is set back one block from the noisy Lombard St in a quieter residential area. This is definitely an older, slightly jaded motel, but the rooms are clean and the staff are extremely friendly. It's close to the shopping on Union St as well.

points_of_interest.name: Travelodge at the Presidio
points_of_interest.description: Standard Travelodge, but set in an excellent location right on the cusp of the Presidio. If you like having the natural world close to your doorstep, then this is the place for you. With its proximity to the Palace of Fine Arts and the historic buildings of the Presidio, it's also a good place to come if you are a fan of architecture.

points_of_interest.name: The Clift Royal Sonesta Hotel
points_of_interest.description: Four-star, 372-room hotel with fitness centre, restaurant, bar, and free Wi-Fi.

points_of_interest.name: Francisco Bay Inn
points_of_interest.description: All of the rooms and hallways are 100% non-smoking. Free parking.

points_of_interest.name: Hotel Drisco
points_of_interest.description: Built in 1903, this is a higher-end, boutique hotel right in the heart of Pacific Heights.

points_of_interest.name: Jackson Court Hotel
points_of_interest.description: This is an opulent three-story brownstone Victorian mansion set in upscale Pacific Heights.  With only 10 rooms, it's more of a B&B than a hotel.  The price includes a continental breakfast and afternoon tea.

points_of_interest.name: Union Street Inn
points_of_interest.description: Edwardian home with spacious airy rooms and a quaint cottage garden in the back.
